# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: carbide
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:carbide/1-4-pentadiyne] Until the late 1960s, no successful synthesis of this seemingly simply preparable molecule was described.
[src:carbide/1-4-pentadiyne] Although long-chain and more complex 1,4-diynes had been synthesized successfully before, synthesis approaches starting from sodium acetylide or the acetylene Grignard reagent and propargyl bromide or methylene chloride failed, even with the inclusion of copper(I) chloride.
[src:carbide/1-4-pentadiyne] Mostly 1,3-pentadiyne was obtained as rearrangement product.
[src:carbide/1-4-pentadiyne] The first successful isolation reacted propargyl bromide and ethynylmagnesium bromide, with a copper(I) chloride catalyst in THF.
[src:carbide/1-4-pentadiyne] This gave a 70% yield in solution, but the product was difficult to separate from the solvent.
[src:carbide/1-4-pentadiyne] Compared to previous attempts, the successful approach included an additional round of flash distillation and gas-liquid chromatography of the distillate.
[src:carbide/1-4-pentadiyne] An improved synthesis method was published by Verkruijsse and Hasselaar in 1979.
[src:carbide/1-4-pentadiyne] Copper chloride was substituted by copper(I) bromide as well as propargyl bromide by propargyl tosylate.
[src:carbide/1-4-pentadiyne] At lower reaction temperatures and fewer by-products, the alkiyne was obtained after multistep extraction.
[src:carbide/1-4-pentadiyne] According to the publication’s authors, this circumvented the problem that the solvent THF and the main compound share similar boiling points.
[src:carbide/1-4-pentadiyne] Moreover, a flash vacuum pyrolysis starting from 3-ethynylcycloprop-1-ene at 550 °C yields the compound and penta-1,2-dien-4-yne as sideproduct.
[src:carbide/1-4-pentadiyne] Alternatively, a photolytic decomposition of cyclopentadienylidene via UV radiation is possible.
[src:carbide/1-4-pentadiyne] The compounds forms also during the exothermic reaction of allene and the ethynyl radical.
[src:carbide/1-4-pentadiyne] This reaction is mainly of interest for astrochemistry.
[src:carbide/1-4-pentadiyne] At room temperature the substance discolors from a colorless to a yellowish liquid, however, storage in diluted solutions at 0 °C is possible for multiple weeks.
[src:carbide/1-4-pentadiyne] While for 1,4-pentadiene the sp2-hybridization leads to a bond angle of 120° between the single and double bond, in 1,4-pentadiyne it is a 180° angle due to the sp-hybrid orbital.
[src:carbide/1-4-pentadiyne] Both triple bonds in 1,4-position destabilize each other according to another study by 3.9 kcal · mol−1, a repulsion between the p orbital lobes close to the sp3-hybridized carbon has been postulated.
[src:carbide/1-4-pentadiyne] According to a QCSID(T) calculation, the alkiyne is destabilized relative to 1,3-pentadiyne by 25 kcal · mol−1.
[src:carbide/1-4-pentadiyne] Although microwave spectroscopy revealed besides a dipole moment of 0.516 D no significant distortions compared to an ideal tetrahedron, three different ionization energies are reported for the π-system.
[src:carbide/1-4-pentadiyne] 1,4-pentadiyne is a common starting material for the synthesis of heterobenzenes such as stiba-, arsa- and phosphabenzene and their substituted derivates.
[src:carbide/acetylide] In chemistry, an **acetylide** is a compound that can be viewed as the result of replacing one or both hydrogen atoms of acetylene (ethyne) HC≡CH by metallic or other cations.
[src:carbide/acetylide] Calcium carbide is an important industrial compound, which has long been used to produce acetylene for welding and illumination.
[src:carbide/acetylide] It is also a major precursor to vinyl chloride.
[src:carbide/acetylide] Other acetylides are reagents in organic synthesis.
[src:carbide/acetylide] It applies to an acetylene RC≡CM, where R = H or a side chain that is usually organic.
[src:carbide/acetylide] The nomenclature can be ambiguous with regards to the distinction between compounds of the types MC2R and M2C2.
[src:carbide/acetylide] When both hydrogens of acetylene are replaced by metals, the compound can also be called carbide, e.g., calcium carbide Ca2+[−C≡C−], which is calcium acetylide.
[src:carbide/acetylide] When only one hydrogen atom is replaced, the anion may be called **hydrogen acetylide** or the prefix *mono*- may be attached to the metal, as in monosodium acetylide or sodium hydrogen acetylide, Na+[−C≡CH].
[src:carbide/acetylide] Metal acetylide may be described as salts, but that description rarely comports with crystallographic analysis.
[src:carbide/acetylide] In the absence of additional ligands, metal acetylides adopt polymeric structures wherein the acetylide groups are bridging ligands.
[src:carbide/acetylide] Alkali metal acetylides have the general formula [M2C2 (M = Li, Na, K, etc).They are sometimes represented as [M+]2[−C≡C−] but the C---M bonding might also be described as polar covalent.
[src:carbide/acetylide] They dissolve without decomposition in ammonia.
[src:carbide/acetylide] Such solutions are proposed to contain solvated −C≡C− ions.
[src:carbide/acetylide] Alkali metal and alkaline earth metal acetylides have the general formula [M'C2 (M' = Mg, Ca, etc).
[src:carbide/acetylide] Rather than salt-like, they can be considered Zintl phase compounds, containing −C≡C− ions, with a triple bond between the two carbon atoms.
[src:carbide/acetylide] The −C≡C− ion has a closed shell ground state of 1Σ+ g, making it isoelectronic to a neutral molecule N2, which may afford it some gas-phase stability.
[src:carbide/acetylide] Acetylides of the transition metals, show evidence of covalent character, e. g. for being neither dissolved nor decomposed by water and by radically different chemical reactions.
[src:carbide/acetylide] Even the stoichiometrically simple silver acetylide and copper acetylide appear highly covalent.
[src:carbide/acetylide] The inventory of such complexes numbers in the hundreds.
[src:carbide/acetylide] The acetylide π* antibonding orbitals are generally too high-energy for substantial metal-ligand backbonding, but still do hybridize with the metal *d* orbitals.
[src:carbide/acetylide] Consequently metal-to-ligand charge transfer excitations lie at low levels in the compounds' spectra.
[src:carbide/acetylide] Monopotassium and monosodium acetylide can be prepared by reacting acetylene with bases like sodium amide or with the elemental metals, often at room temperature and atmospheric pressure.
[src:carbide/acetylide] Copper(I) acetylide can be prepared by passing acetylene through an aqueous solution of copper(I) chloride because of a low solubility equilibrium.
[src:carbide/acetylide] Similarly, silver acetylides can be obtained from silver nitrate.
[src:carbide/acetylide] In organic synthesis, acetylides are usually prepared by treating acetylene and alkynes with organometallic or inorganic bases.
[src:carbide/acetylide] Classically, liquid ammonia was used as solvent for deprotonations, but ethers are now more commonly used.
[src:carbide/acetylide] Calcium carbide is prepared industrially by heating carbon with lime (calcium oxide) at approximately 2,000 °C.
[src:carbide/acetylide] A similar process can be used to produce lithium carbide.
[src:carbide/acetylide] Dilithium acetylide, Li2C2, competes with the preparation of the monolithium derivative LiC2H.
[src:carbide/acetylide] Acetylides of the type RC≡CM are widely used in alkynylations in organic chemistry.
[src:carbide/acetylide] They are nucleophiles that add to a variety of electrophilic and unsaturated substrates.
[src:carbide/acetylide] A classic application is the Favorskii reaction, such as in the sequence shown below.
[src:carbide/acetylide] Here ethyl propiolate is deprotonated by *n*-butyllithium to give the corresponding lithium acetylide.
[src:carbide/acetylide] This acetylide adds to the carbonyl center of cyclopentanone.
[src:carbide/acetylide] Hydrolysis liberates the alkynyl alcohol.
[src:carbide/acetylide] The dimerization of acetylene to vinylacetylene proceeds by insertion of acetylene into a copper(I) acetylide complex.
[src:carbide/acetylide] The copper-catalyzed Click reaction of terminal alkynes and azides proceeds via copper(I) acetylide intermediates.
[src:carbide/acetylide] Acetylides are sometimes used as intermediates in coupling reactions.
[src:carbide/acetylide] Examples include Sonogashira coupling, Cadiot-Chodkiewicz coupling, Glaser coupling and Eglinton coupling.
[src:carbide/acetylide] Some acetylides are notoriously explosive.
[src:carbide/acetylide] Formation of acetylides poses a risk in handling of gaseous acetylene in presence of metals such as mercury, silver or copper, or alloys with their high content (brass, bronze, silver solder).
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The **actinide** (/ˈæktɪnaɪd/) or **actinoid** (/ˈæktɪnɔɪd/) series encompasses at least the 14 metallic chemical elements in the 5f series, with atomic numbers from 89 to 102, actinium through nobelium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Number 103, lawrencium, is also generally included despite being part of the 6d transition series.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The actinide series derives its name from the first element in the series, actinium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The informal chemical symbol **An** is used in general discussions of actinide chemistry to refer to any actinide.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The 1985 IUPAC *Red Book* recommends that *actinoid* be used rather than *actinide*, since the suffix *-ide* normally indicates a negative ion.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] However, owing to widespread current use, *actinide* is still allowed.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Actinium through nobelium are f-block elements, while lawrencium is a d-block element and a transition metal.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The series mostly corresponds to the filling of the 5f electron shell, although as isolated atoms in the ground state many have anomalous configurations involving the filling of the 6d shell due to interelectronic repulsion.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] In comparison with the lanthanides, also mostly f-block elements, the actinides show much more variable valence.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] They all have very large atomic and ionic radii and exhibit an unusually large range of physical properties.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] While actinium and the late actinides (from curium onwards) behave similarly to the lanthanides, the elements thorium, protactinium, and uranium are much more similar to transition metals in their chemistry, with neptunium, plutonium, and americium occupying an intermediate position.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] All actinides are radioactive and release energy upon radioactive decay; naturally occurring uranium and thorium, and synthetically produced plutonium are the most abundant actinides on Earth.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] These have been used in nuclear reactors, and uranium and plutonium are critical elements of nuclear weapons.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Uranium and thorium also have diverse current or historical uses, and americium is used in the ionization chambers of most modern smoke detectors.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Due to their long half-lives, only thorium and uranium are found on Earth and astrophysically in substantial quantities.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The radioactive decay of uranium produces transient amounts of actinium and protactinium, and atoms of neptunium and plutonium are occasionally produced from transmutation reactions in uranium ores.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The other actinides are purely synthetic elements.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Nuclear weapons tests have released at least six actinides heavier than plutonium into the environment; analysis of debris from the 1952 first test of a hydrogen bomb showed the presence of americium, curium, berkelium, californium, and the discovery of einsteinium and fermium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] In presentations of the periodic table, the f-block elements are customarily shown as two additional rows below the main body of the table.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] This convention is entirely a matter of aesthetics and formatting practicality; a rarely used wide-formatted periodic table inserts the 4f and 5f series in their proper places, as parts of the table's sixth and seventh rows (periods).
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Like the lanthanides, the actinides form a family of elements with similar properties.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Within the actinides, there are two overlapping groups: transuranium elements, which follow uranium in the periodic table, and transplutonium elements, which follow plutonium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Compared to the lanthanides, which (except for promethium) are found in nature in appreciable quantities, most actinides are rare.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Most do not occur in nature, and of those that do, only thorium and uranium do so in more than trace quantities.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The most abundant or easily synthesized actinides are uranium and thorium, followed by plutonium, americium, actinium, protactinium, neptunium, and curium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The existence of transuranium elements was suggested in 1934 by Enrico Fermi, based on his experiments.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] However, even though four actinides were known by that time, it was not yet understood that they formed a family similar to lanthanides.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The prevailing view that dominated early research into transuranics was that they were regular elements in the 7th period, with thorium, protactinium and uranium corresponding to 6th-period hafnium, tantalum and tungsten, respectively.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Synthesis of transuranics gradually undermined this point of view.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] By 1944, an observation that curium failed to exhibit oxidation states above 4 (whereas its supposed 6th period homolog, platinum, can reach oxidation state of 6) prompted Glenn Seaborg to formulate an "actinide hypothesis".
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] At present, there are two major methods of producing isotopes of transplutonium elements: (1) irradiation of the lighter elements with neutrons; (2) irradiation with accelerated charged particles.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The first method is more important for applications, as only neutron irradiation using nuclear reactors allows the production of sizeable amounts of synthetic actinides; however, it is limited to relatively light elements.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The advantage of the second method is that elements heavier than plutonium, as well as neutron-deficient isotopes, can be obtained, which are not formed during neutron irradiation.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] In 1962–1966, there were attempts in the United States to produce transplutonium isotopes using a series of six underground nuclear explosions.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Small samples of rock were extracted from the blast area immediately after the test to study the explosion products, but no isotopes with mass number greater than 257 could be detected, despite predictions that such isotopes would have relatively long half-lives of α-decay.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] This non-observation was attributed to spontaneous fission owing to the large speed of the products and to other decay channels, such as neutron emission and nuclear fission.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Uranium and thorium were the first actinides discovered.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Uranium was identified in 1789 by the German chemist Martin Heinrich Klaproth in pitchblende ore.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] He named it after the planet Uranus, which had been discovered eight years earlier.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Klaproth was able to precipitate a yellow compound (likely sodium diuranate) by dissolving pitchblende in nitric acid and neutralizing the solution with sodium hydroxide.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] He then reduced the obtained yellow powder with charcoal, and extracted a black substance that he mistook for metal.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Sixty years later, the French scientist Eugène-Melchior Péligot identified it as uranium oxide.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] He also isolated the first sample of uranium metal by heating uranium tetrachloride with metallic potassium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The atomic mass of uranium was then calculated as 120, but Dmitri Mendeleev in 1872 corrected it to 240 using his periodicity laws.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] This value was confirmed experimentally in 1882 by K.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Thorium oxide was discovered by Friedrich Wöhler in the mineral thorianite, which was found in Norway (1827).
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Jöns Jacob Berzelius characterized this material in more detail in 1828.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] By reduction of thorium tetrachloride with potassium, he isolated the metal and named it thorium after the Norse god of thunder and lightning Thor.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The same isolation method was later used by Péligot for uranium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Actinium was discovered in 1899 by André-Louis Debierne, an assistant of Marie Curie, in the pitchblende waste left after removal of radium and polonium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] He described the substance (in 1899) as similar to titanium and (in 1900) as similar to thorium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The discovery of actinium by Debierne was however questioned in 1971 and 2000, arguing that Debierne's publications in 1904 contradicted his earlier work of 1899–1900.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] This view instead credits the 1902 work of Friedrich Oskar Giesel, who discovered a radioactive element named *emanium* that behaved similarly to lanthanum.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The name actinium comes from the Ancient Greek: ακτίς, ακτίνος (aktis, aktinos), meaning beam or ray.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] This metal was discovered not by its own radiation but by the radiation of the daughter products.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Owing to the close similarity of actinium and lanthanum and low abundance, pure actinium could only be produced in 1950.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The term actinide was probably introduced by Victor Goldschmidt in 1937.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Protactinium was possibly isolated in 1900 by William Crookes.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] It was first identified in 1913, when Kasimir Fajans and Oswald Helmuth Göhring encountered the short-lived isotope 234mPa (half-life 1.17 minutes) during their studies of the 238U decay chain.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The name was shortened to *protactinium* in 1949.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] This element was little characterized until 1960, when Alfred Maddock and his co-workers in the U.K. isolated 130 grams of protactinium from 60 tonnes of waste left after extraction of uranium from its ore.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Neptunium (named for the planet Neptune, the next planet out from Uranus, after which uranium was named) was discovered by Edwin McMillan and Philip H.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Abelson in 1940 in Berkeley, California.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] They produced the 239Np isotope (half-life 2.4 days) by bombarding uranium with slow neutrons.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] It was the first transuranium element produced synthetically.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Transuranium elements do not occur in sizeable quantities in nature and are commonly synthesized via nuclear reactions conducted with nuclear reactors.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] This synthesis reaction was used by Fermi and his collaborators in their design of the reactors located at the Hanford Site, which produced significant amounts of plutonium-239 for the nuclear weapons of the Manhattan Project and the United States' post-war nuclear arsenal.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Actinides with the highest mass numbers are synthesized by bombarding uranium, plutonium, curium and californium with ions of nitrogen, oxygen, carbon, neon or boron in a particle accelerator.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The first isotopes of transplutonium elements, americium-241 and curium-242, were synthesized in 1944 by Glenn T.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The americium-241 and curium-242 isotopes also were produced by irradiating plutonium in a nuclear reactor.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The latter element was named after Marie Curie and her husband Pierre who are noted for discovering radium and for their work in radioactivity.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Bombarding curium-242 with α-particles resulted in an isotope of californium 245Cf in 1950, and a similar procedure yielded berkelium-243 from americium-241 in 1949.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The new elements were named after Berkeley, California, by analogy with its lanthanide homologue terbium, which was named after the village of Ytterby in Sweden.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Cunningham obtained the first bulk chemical compound of a transplutonium element, namely americium hydroxide.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Over the few years, milligram quantities of americium and microgram amounts of curium were accumulated that allowed production of isotopes of berkelium and californium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Sizeable amounts of these elements were produced in 1958, and the first californium compound (0.3 μg of CfOCl) was obtained in 1960 by B.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Einsteinium and fermium were identified in 1952–1953 in the fallout from the "Ivy Mike" nuclear test (1 November 1952), the first successful test of a hydrogen bomb.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Instantaneous exposure of uranium-238 to a large neutron flux resulting from the explosion produced heavy isotopes of uranium, which underwent a series of beta decays to nuclides such as einsteinium-253 and fermium-255.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The discovery of the new elements and the new data on neutron capture were initially kept secret on the orders of the US military until 1955 due to Cold War tensions.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Nevertheless, the Berkeley team were able to prepare einsteinium and fermium by civilian means, through the neutron bombardment of plutonium-239, and published this work in 1954 with the disclaimer that it was not the first studies that had been carried out on those elements.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The "Ivy Mike" studies were declassified and published in 1955.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The first significant (submicrogram) amounts of einsteinium were produced in 1961 by Cunningham and colleagues, but this has not been done for fermium yet.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The first isotope of mendelevium, 256Md (half-life 87 min), was synthesized by Albert Ghiorso, Glenn T.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Seaborg, Gregory Robert Choppin, Bernard G.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Harvey and Stanley Gerald Thompson when they bombarded an 253Es target with alpha particles in the 60-inch cyclotron of Berkeley Radiation Laboratory; this was the first isotope of any element to be synthesized one atom at a time.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] There were several attempts to obtain isotopes of nobelium by Swedish (1957) and American (1958) groups, but the first reliable result was the synthesis of 256No by the Russian group of Georgy Flyorov in 1965, as acknowledged by the IUPAC in 1992.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] In their experiments, Flyorov et al. bombarded uranium-238 with neon-22.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] In 1961, Ghiorso et al. obtained the first isotope of lawrencium by irradiating californium (mostly californium-252) with boron-10 and boron-11 ions.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The mass number of this isotope was not clearly established (possibly 258 or 259) at the time.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] In 1965, 256Lr was synthesized by Flyorov et al. from 243Am and 18O.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Thus IUPAC recognized the nuclear physics teams at Dubna and Berkeley as the co-discoverers of lawrencium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Thirty-four isotopes of actinium and eight excited isomeric states of some of its nuclides are known, ranging in mass number from 203 to 236.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Three isotopes, 225Ac, 227Ac and 228Ac, were found in nature and the others were produced in the laboratory; only the three natural isotopes are used in applications.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Actinium-225 is a member of the radioactive neptunium series; it was first discovered in 1947 as a decay product of uranium-233 and it is an α-emitter with a half-life of 10 days.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Actinium-225 is less available than actinium-228, but is more promising in radiotracer applications.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Actinium-227 (half-life 21.77 years) occurs in all uranium ores, but in small quantities.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] One gram of uranium (in radioactive equilibrium) contains only 2×10−10 gram of 227Ac.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Actinium-228 is a member of the radioactive thorium series formed by the decay of 228Ra; it is a β− emitter with a half-life of 6.15 hours.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] In one tonne of thorium there is 5×10−8 gram of 228Ac.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] There are 32 known isotopes of thorium ranging in mass number from 207 to 238.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Of these, the longest-lived is 232Th, whose half-life of 1.4×1010 years means that it still exists in nature as a primordial nuclide.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The next longest-lived is 230Th, an intermediate decay product of 238U with a half-life of 75,400 years.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Several other thorium isotopes have half-lives over a day; all of these are also transient in the decay chains of 232Th, 235U, and 238U.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Twenty-nine isotopes of protactinium are known with mass numbers 211–239 as well as three excited isomeric states.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Only 231Pa and 234Pa have been found in nature.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] All the isotopes have short lifetimes, except for protactinium-231 (half-life 32,760 years).
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The most important isotopes are 231Pa and 233Pa, which is an intermediate product in obtaining uranium-233 and is the most affordable among artificial isotopes of protactinium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] 233Pa has convenient half-life and energy of γ-radiation, and thus was used in most studies of protactinium chemistry.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Protactinium-233 is a β-emitter with a half-life of 26.97 days.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] There are 27 known isotopes of uranium, having mass numbers 215–242 (except 220).
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Three of them, 234U, 235U and 238U, are present in appreciable quantities in nature.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Among others, the most important is 233U, which is a final product of transformation of 232Th irradiated by slow neutrons.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] 233U has a much higher fission efficiency by low-energy (thermal) neutrons, compared e.g. with 235U.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Most uranium chemistry studies were carried out on uranium-238 owing to its long half-life of 4.4×109 years.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] There are 25 isotopes of neptunium with mass numbers 219–244 (except 221); they are all highly radioactive.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The most popular among scientists are long-lived 237Np (t1/2 = 2.20×106 years) and short-lived 239Np, 238Np (t1/2 ~ 2 days).
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] There are 21 known isotopes of plutonium, having mass numbers 227–247.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The most stable isotope of plutonium is 244Pu with half-life of 8.13×107 years.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Eighteen isotopes of americium are known with mass numbers from 229 to 247 (with the exception of 231).
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The most important are 241Am and 243Am, which are alpha-emitters and also emit soft, but intense γ-rays; both of them can be obtained in an isotopically pure form.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Chemical properties of americium were first studied with 241Am, but later shifted to 243Am, which is almost 20 times less radioactive.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The disadvantage of 243Am is production of the short-lived daughter isotope 239Np, which has to be considered in the data analysis.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Among 19 isotopes of curium, ranging in mass number from 233 to 251, the most accessible are 242Cm and 244Cm; they are α-emitters, but with much shorter lifetime than the americium isotopes.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] These isotopes emit almost no γ-radiation, but undergo spontaneous fission with the associated emission of neutrons.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] More long-lived isotopes of curium (245–248Cm, all α-emitters) are formed as a mixture during neutron irradiation of plutonium or americium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Upon short irradiation, this mixture is dominated by 246Cm, and then 248Cm begins to accumulate.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Both of these isotopes, especially 248Cm, have a longer half-life (3.48×105 years) and are much more convenient for carrying out chemical research than 242Cm and 244Cm, but they also have a rather high rate of spontaneous fission.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] 247Cm has the longest lifetime among isotopes of curium (1.56×107 years), but is not formed in large quantities because of the strong fission induced by thermal neutrons.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Seventeen isotopes of berkelium have been identified with mass numbers 233, 234, 236, 238, and 240–252.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Only 249Bk is available in large quantities; it has a relatively short half-life of 330 days and emits mostly soft β-particles, which are inconvenient for detection.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Its alpha radiation is rather weak (1.45×10−3% with respect to β-radiation), but is sometimes used to detect this isotope.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] 247Bk is an alpha-emitter with a long half-life of 1,380 years, but it is hard to obtain in appreciable quantities; it is not formed upon neutron irradiation of plutonium because β-decay of curium isotopes with mass number below 248 is not known.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The 20 isotopes of californium with mass numbers 237–256 are formed in nuclear reactors; californium-253 is a β-emitter and the rest are α-emitters.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The isotopes with even mass numbers (250Cf, 252Cf and 254Cf) have a high rate of spontaneous fission, especially 254Cf of which 99.7% decays by spontaneous fission.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Californium-249 has a relatively long half-life (352 years), weak spontaneous fission and strong γ-emission that facilitates its identification.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] 249Cf is not formed in large quantities in a nuclear reactor because of the slow β-decay of the parent isotope 249Bk and a large cross section of interaction with neutrons, but it can be accumulated in the isotopically pure form as the β-decay product of (pre-selected) 249Bk.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Californium produced by reactor-irradiation of plutonium mostly consists of 250Cf and 252Cf, the latter being predominant for large neutron fluences, and its study is hindered by the strong neutron radiation.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Among the 18 known isotopes of einsteinium with mass numbers from 240 to 257, the most affordable is 253Es.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] It is an α-emitter with a half-life of 20.47 days, a relatively weak γ-emission and small spontaneous fission rate as compared with the isotopes of californium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Prolonged neutron irradiation also produces a long-lived isotope 254Es (t1/2 = 275.5 days).
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Twenty isotopes of fermium are known with mass numbers of 241–260.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] 254Fm, 255Fm and 256Fm are α-emitters with a short half-life (hours), which can be isolated in significant amounts.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] 257Fm (t1/2 = 100 days) can accumulate upon prolonged and strong irradiation.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] All these isotopes are characterized by high rates of spontaneous fission.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Among the 17 known isotopes of mendelevium (mass numbers from 244 to 260), the most studied is 256Md, which mainly decays through electron capture (α-radiation is ≈10%) with a half-life of 77 minutes.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Another alpha emitter, 258Md, has a half-life of 53 days.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Both these isotopes are produced from rare einsteinium (253Es and 255Es respectively), that therefore limits their availability.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Long-lived isotopes of nobelium and isotopes of lawrencium (and of heavier elements) have relatively short half-lives.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] For nobelium, 13 isotopes are known, with mass numbers 249–260 and 262.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The chemical properties of nobelium and lawrencium were studied with 255No (t1/2 = 3 min) and 256Lr (t1/2 = 35 s).
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The longest-lived nobelium isotope, 259No, has a half-life of approximately 1 hour.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Lawrencium has 14 known isotopes with mass numbers 251–262, 264, and 266.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The most stable of them is 266Lr with a half-life of 11 hours.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The figure *buildup of actinides* is a table of nuclides with the number of neutrons on the horizontal axis (isotopes) and the number of protons on the vertical axis (elements).
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The red dot divides the nuclides in two groups, so the figure is more compact.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Each nuclide is represented by a square with the mass number of the element and its half-life.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Naturally existing actinide isotopes (Th, U) are marked with a bold border, alpha emitters have a yellow colour, and beta emitters have a blue colour.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Pink indicates electron capture (236Np), whereas white stands for a long-lasting metastable state (242Am).
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] In addition to these neutron- or gamma-induced nuclear reactions, the radioactive conversion of actinide nuclides also affects the nuclide inventory in a reactor.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] These decay types are marked in the figure by diagonal arrows.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The beta-minus decay, marked with an arrow pointing up-left, plays a major role for the balance of the particle densities of the nuclides.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Nuclides decaying by positron emission (beta-plus decay) or electron capture (ϵ) do not occur in a nuclear reactor except as products of knockout reactions; their decays are marked with arrows pointing down-right.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Due to the long half-lives of the given nuclides, alpha decay plays almost no role in the formation and decay of the actinides in a power reactor, as the residence time of the nuclear fuel in the reactor core is rather short (a few years).
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Exceptions are the two relatively short-lived nuclides 242Cm (T1/2 = 163 d) and 236Pu (T1/2 = 2.9 y).
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Only for these two cases, the α decay is marked on the nuclide map by a long arrow pointing down-left.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Thorium and uranium are the most abundant actinides in nature with the respective mass concentrations of 16 ppm and 4 ppm.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Uranium mostly occurs in the Earth's crust as a mixture of its oxides in the mineral uraninite, which is also called pitchblende because of its black color.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] There are several dozens of other uranium minerals such as carnotite (KUO2VO4·3H2O) and autunite (Ca(UO2)2(PO4)2·nH2O).
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The worldwide production of uranium in 2009 amounted to 50,572 tonnes, of which 27.3% was mined in Kazakhstan.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The most abundant thorium minerals are thorianite (ThO2), thorite (ThSiO4) and monazite, ((Th,Ca,Ce)PO4).
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Most thorium minerals contain uranium and vice versa; and they all have significant fraction of lanthanides.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Rich deposits of thorium minerals are located in the United States (440,000 tonnes), Australia and India (~300,000 tonnes each) and Canada (~100,000 tonnes).
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The abundance of actinium in the Earth's crust is only about 5×10−15%.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Actinium is mostly present in uranium-containing, but also in other minerals, though in much smaller quantities.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The content of actinium in most natural objects corresponds to the isotopic equilibrium of parent isotope 235U, and it is not affected by the weak Ac migration.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Protactinium is more abundant (10−12%) in the Earth's crust than actinium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] It was discovered in uranium ore in 1913 by Fajans and Göhring.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] As actinium, the distribution of protactinium follows that of 235U.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The half-life of the longest-lived isotope of neptunium, 237Np, is negligible compared to the age of the Earth.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Thus neptunium is present in nature in negligible amounts produced as intermediate decay products of other isotopes.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Traces of plutonium in uranium minerals were first found in 1942, and the more systematic results on 239Pu are summarized in the table (no other plutonium isotopes could be detected in those samples).
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The upper limit of abundance of the longest-living isotope of plutonium, 244Pu, is 3×10−20%.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Plutonium could not be detected in samples of lunar soil.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Owing to its scarcity in nature, most plutonium is produced synthetically.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Owing to the low abundance of actinides, their extraction is a complex, multistep process.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Fluorides of actinides are usually used because they are insoluble in water and can be easily separated with redox reactions.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Among the actinides, thorium and uranium are the easiest to isolate.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Thorium is extracted mostly from monazite: thorium pyrophosphate (ThP2O7) is reacted with nitric acid, and the produced thorium nitrate treated with tributyl phosphate.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Rare-earth impurities are separated by increasing the pH in sulfate solution.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] In another extraction method, monazite is decomposed with a 45% aqueous solution of sodium hydroxide at 140 °C.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Mixed metal hydroxides are extracted first, filtered at 80 °C, washed with water and dissolved with concentrated hydrochloric acid.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Next, the acidic solution is neutralized with hydroxides to pH = 5.8 that results in precipitation of thorium hydroxide (Th(OH)4) contaminated with ~3% of rare-earth hydroxides; the rest of rare-earth hydroxides remains in solution.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Thorium hydroxide is dissolved in an inorganic acid and then purified from the rare earth elements.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Sometimes thorium is extracted by electrolysis of a fluoride in a mixture of sodium and potassium chloride at 700–800 °C in a graphite crucible.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Highly pure thorium can be extracted from its iodide with the crystal bar process.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Uranium is extracted from its ores in various ways.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] In one method, the ore is burned and then reacted with nitric acid to convert uranium into a dissolved state.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Treating the solution with a solution of tributyl phosphate (TBP) in kerosene transforms uranium into an organic form UO2(NO3)2(TBP)2.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The insoluble impurities are filtered and the uranium is extracted by reaction with hydroxides as (NH4)2U2O7 or with hydrogen peroxide as UO4·2H2O.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] When the uranium ore is rich in such minerals as dolomite, magnesite, etc., those minerals consume much acid.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] In this case, the carbonate method is used for uranium extraction.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Its main component is an aqueous solution of sodium carbonate, which converts uranium into a complex [UO2(CO3)3]4−, which is stable in aqueous solutions at low concentrations of hydroxide ions.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The advantages of the sodium carbonate method are that the chemicals have low corrosivity (compared to nitrates) and that most non-uranium metals precipitate from the solution.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The disadvantage is that tetravalent uranium compounds precipitate as well.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] This equation suggests that the best solvent for the uranyl carbonate processing is a mixture of carbonate with bicarbonate.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] At high pH, this results in precipitation of diuranate, which is treated with hydrogen in the presence of nickel yielding an insoluble uranium tetracarbonate.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Another separation method uses polymeric resins as a polyelectrolyte.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Ion exchange processes in the resins result in separation of uranium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Uranium from resins is washed with a solution of ammonium nitrate or nitric acid that yields uranyl nitrate, UO2(NO3)2·6H2O.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] To extract plutonium, neutron-irradiated uranium is dissolved in nitric acid, and a reducing agent (FeSO4, or H2O2) is added to the resulting solution.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] This addition changes the oxidation state of plutonium from +6 to +4, while uranium remains in the form of uranyl nitrate (UO2(NO3)2).
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The solution is treated with a reducing agent and neutralized with ammonium carbonate to pH = 8 that results in precipitation of Pu4+ compounds.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] In another method, Pu4+ and UO2+ 2 are first extracted with tributyl phosphate, then reacted with hydrazine washing out the recovered plutonium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] The major difficulty in separation of actinium is the similarity of its properties with those of lanthanum.
[src:carbide/actinide-p01] Thus actinium is either synthesized in nuclear reactions from isotopes of radium or separated using ion-exchange procedures.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Actinides have similar properties to lanthanides.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Just as the 4f electron shells are filled in the lanthanides, the 5f electron shells are filled in the actinides.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Because the 5f, 6d, 7s, and 7p shells are close in energy, many irregular configurations arise; thus, in gas-phase atoms, just as the first 4f electron only appears in cerium, so the first 5f electron appears even later, in protactinium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] However, just as lanthanum is the first element to use the 4f shell in compounds, so actinium is the first element to use the 5f shell in compounds.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The f-shells complete their filling together, at ytterbium and nobelium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The first experimental evidence for the filling of the 5f shell in actinides was obtained by McMillan and Abelson in 1940.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] As in lanthanides (see lanthanide contraction), the ionic radius of actinides monotonically decreases with atomic number (see also actinoid contraction).
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The shift of electron configurations in the gas phase does not always match the chemical behaviour.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] For example, the early-transition-metal-like prominence of the highest oxidation state, corresponding to removal of all valence electrons, extends up to uranium even though the 5f shells begin filling before that.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] On the other hand, electron configurations resembling the lanthanide congeners already begin at plutonium, even though lanthanide-like behaviour does not become dominant until the second half of the series begins at curium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The elements between uranium and curium form a transition between these two kinds of behaviour, where higher oxidation states continue to exist, but lose stability with respect to the +3 state.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The +2 state becomes more important near the end of the series, and is the most stable oxidation state for nobelium, the last 5f element.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Oxidation states rise again only after nobelium, showing that a new series of 6d transition metals has begun: lawrencium shows only the +3 oxidation state, and rutherfordium only the +4 state, making them respectively congeners of lutetium and hafnium in the 5d row.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Colors for the actinides 100–103 are unknown as sufficient quantities have not yet been synthesized.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] All of them are soft and have a silvery color (but tarnish in air), relatively high density and plasticity.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Their electrical resistivity varies between 15 and 150 μΩ·cm.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The hardness of thorium is similar to that of soft steel, so heated pure thorium can be rolled in sheets and pulled into wire.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Thorium is nearly half as dense as uranium and plutonium, but is harder than either of them.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] All actinides are radioactive, paramagnetic, and, with the exception of actinium, have several crystalline phases: plutonium has seven, and uranium, neptunium and californium three.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The crystal structures of protactinium, uranium, neptunium and plutonium do not have clear analogs among the lanthanides and are more similar to those of the 3*d*-transition metals.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] All actinides are pyrophoric, especially when finely divided, that is, they spontaneously ignite upon reaction with air at room temperature.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The melting point of actinides does not have a clear dependence on the number of *f*-electrons.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The unusually low melting point of neptunium and plutonium (~640 °C) is explained by hybridization of 5*f* and 6*d* orbitals and the formation of directional bonds in these metals.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Like the lanthanides, all actinides are highly reactive with halogens and chalcogens; however, the actinides react more easily.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Actinides, especially those with a small number of 5*f*-electrons, are prone to hybridization.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] This is explained by the similarity of the electron energies at the 5*f*, 7*s* and 6*d* shells.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Most actinides exhibit a larger variety of valence states, and the most stable are +6 for uranium, +5 for protactinium and neptunium, +4 for thorium and plutonium and +3 for actinium and other actinides.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Actinium is chemically similar to lanthanum, which is explained by their similar ionic radii and electronic structures.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Like lanthanum, actinium almost always has an oxidation state of +3 in compounds, but it is less reactive and has more pronounced basic properties.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Among other trivalent actinides Ac3+ is least acidic, i.e. has the weakest tendency to hydrolyze in aqueous solutions.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Owing to lack of electrons on 6*d* and 5*f* orbitals, tetravalent thorium compounds are colorless.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] At pH < 3, solutions of thorium salts are dominated by the cations [Th(H2O)8]4+.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The Th4+ ion is relatively large, and depending on the coordination number can have a radius between 0.95 and 1.14 Å.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] As a result, thorium salts have a weak tendency to hydrolyse.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The distinctive ability of thorium salts is their high solubility both in water and polar organic solvents.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Protactinium exhibits two valence states; the +5 is stable, and the +4 state easily oxidizes to protactinium(V).
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Thus tetravalent protactinium in solutions is obtained by the action of strong reducing agents in a hydrogen atmosphere.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Tetravalent protactinium is chemically similar to uranium(IV) and thorium(IV).
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Fluorides, phosphates, hypophosphates, iodates and phenylarsonates of protactinium(IV) are insoluble in water and dilute acids.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The hydrolytic properties of pentavalent protactinium are close to those of tantalum(V) and niobium(V).
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The complex chemical behavior of protactinium is a consequence of the start of the filling of the 5*f* shell in this element.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Uranium has a valence from 3 to 6, the last being most stable.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] In the hexavalent state, uranium is very similar to the group 6 elements.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Many compounds of uranium(IV) and uranium(VI) are non-stoichiometric, i.e. have variable composition.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] For example, the actual chemical formula of uranium dioxide is UO2+x, where *x* varies between −0.4 and 0.32.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Uranium(VI) compounds are weak oxidants.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Most of them contain the linear "uranyl" group, UO2+ 2.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Between 4 and 6 ligands can be accommodated in an equatorial plane perpendicular to the uranyl group.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The uranyl group acts as a hard acid and forms stronger complexes with oxygen-donor ligands than with nitrogen-donor ligands.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] NpO2+ 2 and PuO2+ 2 are also the common form of Np and Pu in the +6 oxidation state.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Uranium(IV) compounds exhibit reducing properties, e.g., they are easily oxidized by atmospheric oxygen.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Uranium(III) is a very strong reducing agent.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Owing to the presence of d-shell, uranium (as well as many other actinides) forms organometallic compounds, such as UIII(C5H5)3 and UIV(C5H5)4.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Neptunium has valence states from 3 to 7, which can be simultaneously observed in solutions.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The most stable state in solution is +5, but the valence +4 is preferred in solid neptunium compounds.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Ions of neptunium are prone to hydrolysis and formation of coordination compounds.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Plutonium also exhibits valence states between 3 and 7 inclusive, and thus is chemically similar to neptunium and uranium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] It is highly reactive, and quickly forms an oxide film in air.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Plutonium reacts with hydrogen even at temperatures as low as 25–50 °C; it also easily forms halides and intermetallic compounds.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Hydrolysis reactions of plutonium ions of different oxidation states are quite diverse.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Plutonium(V) can enter polymerization reactions.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The largest chemical diversity among actinides is observed in americium, which can have valence between 2 and 6.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Divalent americium is obtained only in dry compounds and non-aqueous solutions (acetonitrile).
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Oxidation states +3, +5 and +6 are typical for aqueous solutions, but also in the solid state.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Tetravalent americium forms stable solid compounds (dioxide, fluoride and hydroxide) as well as complexes in aqueous solutions.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] It was reported that in alkaline solution americium can be oxidized to the heptavalent state, but these data proved erroneous.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The most stable valence of americium is 3 in aqueous solution and 3 or 4 in solid compounds.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Valence 3 is dominant in all subsequent elements up to lawrencium (with the exception of nobelium).
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Curium can be tetravalent in solids (fluoride, dioxide).
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Berkelium, along with a valence of +3, also shows the valence of +4, more stable than that of curium; the valence 4 is observed in solid fluoride and dioxide.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The stability of Bk4+ in aqueous solution is close to that of Ce4+.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Only valence 3 was observed for californium, einsteinium and fermium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The divalent state is proven for mendelevium and nobelium, and in nobelium it is more stable than the trivalent state.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Lawrencium shows valence 3 both in solutions and solids.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The redox potential ${\ce {{\mathit {E}}_{\frac {M^{4}+}{AnO2^{2}+}}}}$ increases from −0.32 V in uranium, through 0.34 V (Np) and 1.04 V (Pu) to 1.34 V in americium revealing the increasing reduction ability of the An4+ ion from americium to uranium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] All actinides form AnH3 hydrides of black color with salt-like properties.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Actinides also produce carbides with the general formula of AnC or AnC2 (U2C3 for uranium) as well as sulfides An2S3 and AnS2.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Some actinides can exist in several oxide forms such as An2O3, AnO2, An2O5 and AnO3.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] These bases are poorly soluble in water and by their activity are close to the hydroxides of rare-earth metals.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Np(OH)3 has not yet been synthesized, Pu(OH)3 has a blue color while Am(OH)3 is pink and Cm(OH)3 is colorless.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Bk(OH)3 and Cf(OH)3 are also known, as are tetravalent hydroxides for Np, Pu and Am and pentavalent for Np and Am.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] All compounds of actinium are colorless, except for black actinium sulfide (Ac2S3).
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Dioxides of tetravalent actinides crystallize in the cubic system, same as in calcium fluoride.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Thorium dioxide is a refractory material with the highest melting point among any known oxide (3390 °C).
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Adding 0.8–1% ThO2 to tungsten stabilizes its structure, so the doped filaments have better mechanical stability to vibrations.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] To dissolve ThO2 in acids, it is heated to 500–600 °C; heating above 600 °C produces a very resistant to acids and other reagents form of ThO2.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Small addition of fluoride ions catalyses dissolution of thorium dioxide in acids.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Two protactinium oxides have been obtained: PaO2 (black) and Pa2O5 (white); the former is isomorphic with ThO2 and the latter is easier to obtain.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Both oxides are basic, and Pa(OH)5 is a weak, poorly soluble base.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Decomposition of certain salts of uranium, for example UO2(NO3)·6H2O in air at 400 °C, yields orange or yellow UO3.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] This oxide is amphoteric and forms several hydroxides, the most stable being uranyl hydroxide UO2(OH)2.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Reaction of uranium(VI) oxide with hydrogen results in uranium dioxide, which is similar in its properties with ThO2.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] This oxide is also basic and corresponds to the uranium hydroxide U(OH)4.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Plutonium, neptunium and americium form two basic oxides: An2O3 and AnO2.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Neptunium trioxide is unstable; thus, only Np3O8 could be obtained so far.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] However, the oxides of plutonium and neptunium with the chemical formula AnO2 and An2O3 are well characterized.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Actinides easily react with halogens forming salts with the formulas MX3 and MX4 (X = halogen).
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] So the first berkelium compound, BkCl3, was synthesized in 1962 with an amount of 3 nanograms.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Like the halogens of rare earth elements, actinide chlorides, bromides, and iodides are water-soluble, and fluorides are insoluble.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Uranium easily yields a colorless hexafluoride, which sublimates at a temperature of 56.5 °C; because of its volatility, it is used in the separation of uranium isotopes with gas centrifuge or gaseous diffusion.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Actinide hexafluorides have properties close to anhydrides.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] They are very sensitive to moisture and hydrolyze forming AnO2F2.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The pentachloride and black hexachloride of uranium were synthesized, but they are both unstable.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] However, in these reactions the regenerating hydrogen can react with the metal, forming the corresponding hydride.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Uranium reacts with acids and water much more easily than thorium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Actinide salts can also be obtained by dissolving the corresponding hydroxides in acids.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Nitrates, chlorides, sulfates and perchlorates of actinides are water-soluble.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] When crystallizing from aqueous solutions, these salts form hydrates, such as Th(NO3)4·6H2O, Th(SO4)2·9H2O and Pu2(SO4)3·7H2O.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Salts of high-valence actinides easily hydrolyze.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] So, colorless sulfate, chloride, perchlorate and nitrate of thorium transform into basic salts with formulas Th(OH)2SO4 and Th(OH)3NO3.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The solubility and insolubility of trivalent and tetravalent actinides is like that of lanthanide salts.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] So phosphates, fluorides, oxalates, iodates and carbonates of actinides are weakly soluble in water; they precipitate as hydrates, such as ThF4·3H2O and Th(CrO4)2·3H2O.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Actinides with oxidation state +6, except for the AnO22+-type cations, form [AnO4]2−, [An2O7]2− and other complex anions.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] For example, uranium, neptunium and plutonium form salts of the Na2UO4 (uranate) and (NH4)2U2O7 (diuranate) types.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] In comparison with lanthanides, actinides more easily form coordination compounds, and this ability increases with the actinide valence.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Trivalent actinides do not form fluoride coordination compounds, whereas tetravalent thorium forms K2ThF6, KThF5, and even K5ThF9 complexes.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Thorium also forms the corresponding sulfates (for example Na2SO4·Th(SO4)2·5H2O), nitrates and thiocyanates.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Salts with the general formula An2Th(NO3)6·*n*H2O are of coordination nature, with the coordination number of thorium equal to 12.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Even easier is to produce complex salts of pentavalent and hexavalent actinides.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The most stable coordination compounds of actinides – tetravalent thorium and uranium – are obtained in reactions with diketones, e.g. acetylacetone.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] While actinides have some established daily-life applications, such as in smoke detectors (americium) and gas mantles (thorium), they are mostly used in nuclear weapons and as fuel in nuclear reactors.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The last two areas exploit the property of actinides to release enormous energy in nuclear reactions, which under certain conditions may become self-sustaining chain reactions.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The most important isotope for nuclear power applications is uranium-235.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] It is used in the thermal reactor, and its concentration in natural uranium does not exceed 0.72%.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] This isotope strongly absorbs thermal neutrons releasing much energy.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] One fission act of 1 gram of 235U converts into about 1 MW·day.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Of importance, is that 235 92U emits more neutrons than it absorbs; upon reaching the critical mass, 235 92U enters into a self-sustaining chain reaction.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Other promising actinide isotopes for nuclear power are thorium-232 and its product from the thorium fuel cycle, uranium-233.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Emission of neutrons during the fission of uranium is important not only for maintaining the nuclear chain reaction, but also for the synthesis of the heavier actinides.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Uranium-239 converts via β-decay into plutonium-239, which, like uranium-235, is capable of spontaneous fission.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The world's first nuclear reactors were built not for energy, but for producing plutonium-239 for nuclear weapons.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] About half of produced thorium is used as the light-emitting material of gas mantles.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Thorium is also added into multicomponent alloys of magnesium and zinc.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Mg-Th alloys are light and strong, but also have high melting point and ductility and thus are widely used in the aviation industry and in the production of missiles.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Thorium also has good electron emission properties, with long lifetime and low potential barrier for the emission.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The relative content of thorium and uranium isotopes is widely used to estimate the age of various objects, including stars (see radiometric dating).
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The major application of plutonium has been in nuclear weapons, where the isotope plutonium-239 was a key component due to its ease of fission and availability.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Plutonium-based designs allow reducing the critical mass to about a third of that for uranium-235.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The "Fat Man"-type plutonium bombs produced during the Manhattan Project used explosive compression of plutonium to obtain significantly higher densities than normal, combined with a central neutron source to begin the reaction and increase efficiency.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Thus only 6.2 kg of plutonium was needed for an explosive yield equivalent to 20 kilotons of TNT.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] (See also Nuclear weapon design.) Hypothetically, as little as 4 kg of plutonium—and maybe even less—could be used to make a single atomic bomb using very sophisticated assembly designs.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Plutonium-238 is potentially more efficient isotope for nuclear reactors, since it has smaller critical mass than uranium-235, but it continues to release much thermal energy (0.56 W/g) by decay even when the fission chain reaction is stopped by control rods.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Its application is limited by its high price (about US$1000/g).
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] This isotope has been used in thermopiles and water distillation systems of some space satellites and stations.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Apollo 14) had heaters powered by kilogram quantities of plutonium-238 oxide; this heat is also transformed into electricity with thermopiles.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The decay of plutonium-238 produces relatively harmless alpha particles and is not accompanied by gamma rays.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Therefore, this isotope (~160 mg) is used as the energy source in heart pacemakers where it lasts about 5 times longer than conventional batteries.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Actinium-227 is used as a neutron source.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Its high specific energy (14.5 W/g) and the possibility of obtaining significant quantities of thermally stable compounds are attractive for use in long-lasting thermoelectric generators for remote use.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] 228Ac is used as an indicator of radioactivity in chemical research, as it emits high-energy electrons (2.18 MeV) that can be easily detected.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] 228Ac-228Ra mixtures are widely used as an intense gamma-source in industry and medicine.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Development of self-glowing actinide-doped materials with durable crystalline matrices is a new area of actinide utilization as the addition of alpha-emitting radionuclides to some glasses and crystals may confer luminescence.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Radioactive substances can harm human health via (i) local skin contamination, (ii) internal exposure due to ingestion of radioactive isotopes, and (iii) external overexposure by β-activity and γ-radiation.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Together with radium and transuranium elements, actinium is one of the most dangerous radioactive poisons with high specific α-activity.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The most important feature of actinium is its ability to accumulate and remain in the surface layer of skeletons.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] At the initial stage of poisoning, actinium accumulates in the liver.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Another danger of actinium is that it undergoes radioactive decay faster than being excreted.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Adsorption from the digestive tract is much smaller (~0.05%) for actinium than radium.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Protactinium in the body tends to accumulate in the kidneys and bones.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The maximum safe dose of protactinium in the human body is 0.03 μCi that corresponds to 0.5 micrograms of 231Pa.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] This isotope, which might be present in the air as aerosol, is 2.5×108 times more toxic than hydrocyanic acid.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Plutonium, when entering the body through air, food or blood (e.g. a wound), mostly settles in the lungs, liver and bones with only about 10% going to other organs, and remains there for decades.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The long residence time of plutonium in the body is partly explained by its poor solubility in water.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Some isotopes of plutonium emit ionizing α-radiation, which damages the surrounding cells.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] The median lethal dose (LD50) for 30 days in dogs after intravenous injection of plutonium is 0.32 milligram per kg of body mass, and thus the lethal dose for humans is approximately 22 mg for a person weighing 70 kg; the amount for respiratory exposure should be approximately four times greater.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Another estimate assumes that plutonium is 50 times less toxic than radium, and thus permissible content of plutonium in the body should be 5 μg or 0.3 μCi.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Such amount is nearly invisible under microscope.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] After trials on animals, this maximum permissible dose was reduced to 0.65 μg or 0.04 μCi.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Studies on animals also revealed that the most dangerous plutonium exposure route is through inhalation, after which 5–25% of inhaled substances is retained in the body.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Depending on the particle size and solubility of the plutonium compounds, plutonium is localized either in the lungs or in the lymphatic system, or is absorbed in the blood and then transported to the liver and bones.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Contamination via food is the least likely way.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] In this case, only about 0.05% of soluble and 0.01% of insoluble compounds of plutonium absorbs into blood, and the rest is excreted.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Exposure of damaged skin to plutonium would retain nearly 100% of it.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Using actinides in nuclear fuel, sealed radioactive sources or advanced materials such as self-glowing crystals has many potential benefits.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] However, a serious concern is the extremely high radiotoxicity of actinides and their migration in the environment.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] Use of chemically unstable forms of actinides in MOX and sealed radioactive sources is not appropriate by modern safety standards.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] There is a challenge to develop stable and durable actinide-bearing materials, which provide safe storage, use and final disposal.
[src:carbide/actinide-p02] A key need is application of actinide solid solutions in durable crystalline host phases.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The **alkali metals** consist of the chemical elements lithium (Li), sodium (Na), potassium (K), rubidium (Rb), caesium (Cs), and francium (Fr).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Together with hydrogen they constitute group 1, which lies in the s-block of the periodic table.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] All alkali metals have their outermost electron in an s-orbital: this shared electron configuration results in them having very similar characteristic properties.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Indeed, the alkali metals provide the best example of group trends in properties in the periodic table, with elements exhibiting well-characterised homologous behaviour.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] This family of elements is also known as the **lithium family** after its leading element.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The alkali metals are all shiny, soft, highly reactive metals at standard temperature and pressure and readily lose their outermost electron to form cations with charge +1.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] They can all be cut easily with a knife due to their softness, exposing a shiny surface that tarnishes rapidly in air due to oxidation by atmospheric moisture and oxygen (and in the case of lithium, nitrogen).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Because of their high reactivity, they must be stored under oil to prevent reaction with air, and are found naturally only in salts and never as the free elements.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Caesium, the fifth alkali metal, is the most reactive of all the metals.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] All the alkali metals react with water, with the heavier alkali metals reacting more vigorously than the lighter ones.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Experiments have been conducted to attempt the synthesis of element 119, which is likely to be the next member of the group; none were successful.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Most alkali metals have many different applications.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] One of the best-known applications of the pure elements is the use of rubidium and caesium in atomic clocks, of which caesium atomic clocks form the basis of the second.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] A common application of the compounds of sodium is the sodium-vapour lamp, which emits light very efficiently.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Table salt, or sodium chloride, has been used since antiquity.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Lithium finds use as a psychiatric medication and as an anode in lithium batteries.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Sodium, potassium and possibly lithium are essential elements, having major biological roles as electrolytes, and although the other alkali metals are not essential, they also have various effects on the body, both beneficial and harmful.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Sodium compounds have been known since ancient times; salt (sodium chloride) has been an important commodity in human activities.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] While potash has been used since ancient times, it was not understood for most of its history to be a fundamentally different substance from sodium mineral salts.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Georg Ernst Stahl obtained experimental evidence which led him to suggest the fundamental difference of sodium and potassium salts in 1702, and Henri-Louis Duhamel du Monceau was able to prove this difference in 1736.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The exact chemical composition of potassium and sodium compounds, and the status as chemical element of potassium and sodium, was not known then, and thus Antoine Lavoisier did not include either alkali in his list of chemical elements in 1789.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Pure potassium was first isolated in 1807 in England by Humphry Davy, who derived it from caustic potash (KOH, potassium hydroxide) by the use of electrolysis of the molten salt with the newly invented voltaic pile.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Previous attempts at electrolysis of the aqueous salt were unsuccessful due to potassium's extreme reactivity.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Potassium was the first metal that was isolated by electrolysis.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Later that same year, Davy reported extraction of sodium from the similar substance caustic soda (NaOH, lye) by a similar technique, demonstrating the elements, and thus the salts, to be different.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Petalite (LiAlSi4O10) was discovered in 1800 by the Brazilian chemist José Bonifácio de Andrada in a mine on the island of Utö, Sweden.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] However, it was not until 1817 that Johan August Arfwedson, then working in the laboratory of the chemist Jöns Jacob Berzelius, detected the presence of a new element while analysing petalite ore.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] This new element was noted by him to form compounds similar to those of sodium and potassium, though its carbonate and hydroxide were less soluble in water and more alkaline than the other alkali metals.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] He named the metal inside the material *lithium*.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Lithium, sodium, and potassium were part of the discovery of periodicity, as they are among a series of triads of elements in the same group that were noted by Johann Wolfgang Döbereiner in 1850 as having similar properties.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Rubidium and caesium were the first elements to be discovered using the spectroscope, invented in 1859 by Robert Bunsen and Gustav Kirchhoff.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The next year, they discovered caesium in the mineral water from Bad Dürkheim, Germany.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Their discovery of rubidium came the following year in Heidelberg, Germany, finding it in the mineral lepidolite.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The names of rubidium and caesium come from the most prominent lines in their emission spectra: a bright red line for rubidium (from the Latin word *rubidus*, meaning dark red or bright red), and a sky-blue line for caesium (derived from the Latin word *caesius*, meaning sky-blue).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] His version put all the alkali metals then known (lithium to caesium), as well as copper, silver, and thallium (which show the +1 oxidation state characteristic of the alkali metals), together into a group.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] His table placed hydrogen with the halogens.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] After 1869, Dmitri Mendeleev proposed his periodic table placing lithium at the top of a group with sodium, potassium, rubidium, caesium, and thallium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Two years later, Mendeleev revised his table, placing hydrogen in group 1 above lithium, and also moving thallium to the boron group.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] In this 1871 version, copper, silver, and gold were placed twice, once as part of group IB, and once as part of a "group VIII" encompassing today's groups 8 to 11.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] After the introduction of the 18-column table, the group IB elements were moved to their current position in the d-block, while alkali metals were left in *group IA*.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Later the group's name was changed to *group 1* in 1988.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The trivial name "alkali metals" comes from the fact that the hydroxides of the group 1 elements are all strong alkalis when dissolved in water.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] There were at least four erroneous and incomplete discoveries before Marguerite Perey of the Curie Institute in Paris, France discovered francium in 1939 by purifying a sample of actinium-227, which had been reported to have a decay energy of 220 keV.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] However, Perey noticed decay particles with an energy level below 80 keV.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Perey thought this decay activity might have been caused by a previously unidentified decay product, one that was separated during purification, but emerged again out of the pure actinium-227.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Various tests eliminated the possibility of the unknown element being thorium, radium, lead, bismuth, or thallium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The new product exhibited chemical properties of an alkali metal (such as coprecipitating with caesium salts), which led Perey to believe that it was element 87, caused by the alpha decay of actinium-227.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Perey then attempted to determine the proportion of beta decay to alpha decay in actinium-227.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Her first test put the alpha branching at 0.6%, a figure that she later revised to 1%.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The next element below francium (eka-francium) in the periodic table would be ununennium (Uue), element 119.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The synthesis of ununennium was first attempted in 1985 by bombarding a target of einsteinium-254 with calcium-48 ions at the superHILAC accelerator at the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory in Berkeley, California.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] No atoms were identified, leading to a limiting yield of 300 nb.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] However, given that ununennium is only the first period 8 element on the extended periodic table, it may well be discovered in the near future through other reactions, and indeed an attempt to synthesise it is currently ongoing in Japan.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Currently, none of the period 8 elements has been discovered yet, and it is also possible, due to drip instabilities, that only the lower period 8 elements, up to around element 128, are physically possible.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] No attempts at synthesis have been made for any heavier alkali metals: due to their extremely high atomic number, they would require new, more powerful methods and technology to make.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The Oddo–Harkins rule holds that elements with even atomic numbers are more common than those with odd atomic numbers, with the exception of hydrogen and beryllium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] This rule argues that elements with odd atomic numbers have one unpaired proton and are more likely to capture another, thus increasing their atomic number.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] In elements with even atomic numbers, protons are paired, with each member of the pair offsetting the spin of the other, enhancing stability.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] All the alkali metals have odd atomic numbers and they are not as common as the elements with even atomic numbers adjacent to them (the noble gases and the alkaline earth metals) in the Solar System.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The heavier alkali metals are also less abundant than the lighter ones as the alkali metals from rubidium onward can only be synthesised in supernovae and not in stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The Earth formed from the same cloud of matter that formed the Sun, but the planets acquired different compositions during the formation and evolution of the Solar System.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] In turn, the natural history of the Earth caused parts of this planet to have differing concentrations of the elements.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The mass of the Earth is approximately 5.98×1024 kg.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Due to planetary differentiation, the core region is believed to be primarily composed of iron (88.8%), with smaller amounts of nickel (5.8%), sulfur (4.5%), and less than 1% trace elements.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The alkali metals, due to their high reactivity, do not occur naturally in pure form in nature.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] They are lithophiles and therefore remain close to the Earth's surface because they combine readily with oxygen and so associate strongly with silica, forming relatively low-density minerals that do not sink down into the Earth's core.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Potassium, rubidium and caesium are also incompatible elements due to their large ionic radii.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Sodium and potassium are very abundant on Earth, both being among the ten most common elements in Earth's crust; sodium makes up approximately 2.6% of the Earth's crust measured by weight, making it the sixth most abundant element overall and the most abundant alkali metal.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Potassium makes up approximately 1.5% of the Earth's crust and is the seventh most abundant element.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Sodium is found in many different minerals, of which the most common is ordinary salt (sodium chloride), which occurs in vast quantities dissolved in seawater.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Other solid deposits include halite, amphibole, cryolite, nitratine, and zeolite.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Many of these solid deposits occur as a result of ancient seas evaporating, which still occurs now in places such as Utah's Great Salt Lake and the Dead Sea.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Despite its chemical similarity, lithium typically does not occur together with sodium or potassium due to its smaller size.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Due to its relatively low reactivity, it can be found in seawater in large amounts; it is estimated that lithium concentration in seawater is approximately 0.14 to 0.25 parts per million (ppm) or 25 micromolar.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Its diagonal relationship with magnesium often allows it to replace magnesium in ferromagnesium minerals, where its crustal concentration is about 18 ppm, comparable to that of gallium and niobium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Commercially, the most important lithium mineral is spodumene, which occurs in large deposits worldwide.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Rubidium is approximately as abundant as zinc and more abundant than copper.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] It occurs naturally in the minerals leucite, pollucite, carnallite, zinnwaldite, and lepidolite, although none of these contain only rubidium and no other alkali metals.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Caesium is more abundant than some commonly known elements, such as antimony, cadmium, tin, and tungsten, but is much less abundant than rubidium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Francium-223, the only naturally occurring isotope of francium, is the product of the alpha decay of actinium-227 and can be found in trace amounts in uranium minerals.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] In a given sample of uranium, there is estimated to be only one francium atom for every 1018 uranium atoms.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] It has been calculated that there are at most 30 grams of francium in the earth's crust at any time, due to its extremely short half-life of 22 minutes.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The physical and chemical properties of the alkali metals can be readily explained by their having an ns1 valence electron configuration, which results in weak metallic bonding.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Hence, all the alkali metals are soft and have low densities, melting and boiling points, as well as heats of sublimation, vaporisation, and dissociation.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] They all crystallise in the body-centered cubic crystal structure, and have distinctive flame colours because their outer s electron is very easily excited.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Indeed, these flame test colours are the most common way of identifying them since all their salts with common ions are soluble.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The ns1 configuration also results in the alkali metals having very large atomic and ionic radii, as well as very high thermal and electrical conductivity.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Their chemistry is dominated by the loss of their lone valence electron in the outermost s-orbital to form the +1 oxidation state, due to the ease of ionising this electron and the very high second ionisation energy.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Most of the chemistry has been observed only for the first five members of the group.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The chemistry of francium is not well established due to its extreme radioactivity; thus, the presentation of its properties here is limited.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] What little is known about francium shows that it is very close in behaviour to caesium, as expected.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The physical properties of francium are even sketchier because the bulk element has never been observed; hence any data that may be found in the literature are certainly speculative extrapolations.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The alkali metals are more similar to each other than the elements in any other group are to each other.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Indeed, the similarity is so great that it is quite difficult to separate potassium, rubidium, and caesium, due to their similar ionic radii; lithium and sodium are more distinct.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] For instance, when moving down the table, all known alkali metals show increasing atomic radius, decreasing electronegativity, increasing reactivity, and decreasing melting and boiling points as well as heats of fusion and vaporisation.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] In general, their densities increase when moving down the table, with the exception that potassium is less dense than sodium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] One of the very few properties of the alkali metals that does not display a very smooth trend is their reduction potentials: lithium's value is anomalous, being more negative than the others.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The stable alkali metals are all silver-coloured metals except for caesium, which has a pale golden tint: it is one of only three metals that are clearly coloured (the other two being copper and gold).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Additionally, the heavy alkaline earth metals calcium, strontium, and barium, as well as the divalent lanthanides europium and ytterbium, are pale yellow, though the colour is much less prominent than it is for caesium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Their lustre tarnishes rapidly in air due to oxidation.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] All the alkali metals are highly reactive and are never found in elemental forms in nature.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Because of this, they are usually stored in mineral oil or kerosene (paraffin oil).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] They react aggressively with the halogens to form the alkali metal halides, which are white ionic crystalline compounds that are all soluble in water except lithium fluoride (LiF).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The alkali metals also react with water to form strongly alkaline hydroxides and thus should be handled with great care.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The heavier alkali metals react more vigorously than the lighter ones; for example, when dropped into water, caesium produces a larger explosion than potassium if the same number of moles of each metal is used.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The alkali metals have the lowest first ionisation energies in their respective periods of the periodic table because of their low effective nuclear charge and the ability to attain a noble gas configuration by losing just one electron.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Not only do the alkali metals react with water, but also with proton donors like alcohols and phenols, gaseous ammonia, and alkynes, the last demonstrating the phenomenal degree of their reactivity.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Their great power as reducing agents makes them very useful in liberating other metals from their oxides or halides.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The second ionisation energy of all of the alkali metals is very high as it is in a full shell that is also closer to the nucleus; thus, they almost always lose a single electron, forming cations.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The alkalide anions have filled s-subshells, which gives them enough stability to exist.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] All the stable alkali metals except lithium are known to be able to form alkalides, and the alkalides have much theoretical interest due to their unusual stoichiometry and low ionisation potentials.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Alkalides are chemically similar to the electrides, which are salts with trapped electrons acting as anions.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] In aqueous solution, the alkali metal ions form aqua ions of the formula [M(H2O)*n*]+, where *n* is the solvation number.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Their coordination numbers and shapes agree well with those expected from their ionic radii.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] In aqueous solution the water molecules directly attached to the metal ion are said to belong to the first coordination sphere, also known as the first, or primary, solvation shell.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The bond between a water molecule and the metal ion is a dative covalent bond, with the oxygen atom donating both electrons to the bond.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Each coordinated water molecule may be attached by hydrogen bonds to other water molecules.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The latter are said to reside in the second coordination sphere.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] There are also probably six water molecules in the primary solvation sphere of the sodium ion, forming the octahedral [Na(H2O)6]+ ion.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The chemistry of lithium shows several differences from that of the rest of the group as the small Li+ cation polarises anions and gives its compounds a more covalent character.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Lithium and magnesium have a diagonal relationship due to their similar atomic radii, so that they show some similarities.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] For example, lithium forms a stable nitride, a property common among all the alkaline earth metals (magnesium's group) but unique among the alkali metals.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] In addition, among their respective groups, only lithium and magnesium form organometallic compounds with significant covalent character (e.g.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Lithium fluoride is the only alkali metal halide that is poorly soluble in water, and lithium hydroxide is the only alkali metal hydroxide that is not deliquescent.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Conversely, lithium perchlorate and other lithium salts with large anions that cannot be polarised are much more stable than the analogous compounds of the other alkali metals, probably because Li+ has a high solvation energy.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] This effect also means that most simple lithium salts are commonly encountered in hydrated form, because the anhydrous forms are extremely hygroscopic: this allows salts like lithium chloride and lithium bromide to be used in dehumidifiers and air-conditioners.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Francium is also predicted to show some differences due to its high atomic weight, causing its electrons to travel at considerable fractions of the speed of light and thus making relativistic effects more prominent.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Thus, contrary to expectation, caesium is the most reactive of the alkali metals, not francium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Some of the few properties of francium that have been predicted taking relativity into account are the electron affinity (47.2 kJ/mol) and the enthalpy of dissociation of the Fr2 molecule (42.1 kJ/mol).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The CsFr molecule is polarised as Cs+Fr−, showing that the 7s subshell of francium is much more strongly affected by relativistic effects than the 6s subshell of caesium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Additionally, francium superoxide (FrO2) is expected to have significant covalent character, unlike the other alkali metal superoxides, because of bonding contributions from the 6p electrons of francium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] All the alkali metals have odd atomic numbers; hence, their isotopes must be either odd–odd (both proton and neutron number are odd) or odd–even (proton number is odd, but neutron number is even).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Odd–odd nuclei have even mass numbers, whereas odd–even nuclei have odd mass numbers.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Odd–odd primordial nuclides are rare because most odd–odd nuclei are highly unstable with respect to beta decay, because the decay products are even–even, and are therefore more strongly bound, due to nuclear pairing effects.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Due to the great rarity of odd–odd nuclei, almost all the primordial isotopes of the alkali metals are odd–even (the exceptions being the light stable isotope lithium-6 and the long-lived radioisotope potassium-40).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] An effect of the instability of an odd number of either type of nucleons is that odd-numbered elements, such as the alkali metals, tend to have fewer stable isotopes than even-numbered elements.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Of the 26 monoisotopic elements that have only a single stable isotope, all but one have an odd atomic number and all but one also have an even number of neutrons.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Beryllium is the single exception to both rules, due to its low atomic number.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Caesium was also thought to be radioactive in the early 20th century, although it has no naturally occurring radioisotopes.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] (Francium had not been discovered yet at that time.) The natural long-lived radioisotope of potassium, potassium-40, makes up about 0.012% of natural potassium, and thus natural potassium is weakly radioactive.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] This natural radioactivity became a basis for a mistaken claim of the discovery for element 87 (the next alkali metal after caesium) in 1925.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Natural rubidium is similarly slightly radioactive, with 27.83% being the long-lived radioisotope rubidium-87.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Caesium-137, with a half-life of 30.17 years, is one of the two principal medium-lived fission products, along with strontium-90, which are responsible for most of the radioactivity of spent nuclear fuel after several years of cooling, up to several hundred years after use.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] It constitutes most of the radioactivity still left from the Chernobyl accident.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Caesium-137 undergoes high-energy beta decay and eventually becomes stable barium-137.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] It is a strong emitter of gamma radiation.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Caesium-137 has a very low rate of neutron capture and cannot be feasibly disposed of in this way, but must be allowed to decay.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Caesium-137 has been used as a tracer in hydrologic studies, analogous to the use of tritium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Small amounts of caesium-134 and caesium-137 were released into the environment during nearly all nuclear weapon tests and some nuclear accidents, most notably the Goiânia accident and the Chernobyl disaster.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] As of 2005, caesium-137 is the principal source of radiation in the zone of alienation around the Chernobyl nuclear power plant.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The atomic radii of the alkali metals increase going down the group.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Because of the shielding effect, when an atom has more than one electron shell, each electron feels electric repulsion from the other electrons as well as electric attraction from the nucleus.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] In the alkali metals, the outermost electron only feels a net charge of +1, as some of the nuclear charge (which is equal to the atomic number) is cancelled by the inner electrons; the number of inner electrons of an alkali metal is always one less than the nuclear charge.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Therefore, the only factor which affects the atomic radius of the alkali metals is the number of electron shells.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Since this number increases down the group, the atomic radius must also increase down the group.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The ionic radii of the alkali metals are much smaller than their atomic radii.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] This is because the outermost electron of the alkali metals is in a different electron shell than the inner electrons, and thus when it is removed the resulting atom has one fewer electron shell and is smaller.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Additionally, the effective nuclear charge has increased, and thus the electrons are attracted more strongly towards the nucleus and the ionic radius decreases.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The first ionisation energy of an element or molecule is the energy required to move the most loosely held electron from one mole of gaseous atoms of the element or molecules to form one mole of gaseous ions with electric charge +1.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The factors affecting the first ionisation energy are the nuclear charge, the amount of shielding by the inner electrons and the distance from the most loosely held electron from the nucleus, which is always an outer electron in main group elements.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The first two factors change the effective nuclear charge the most loosely held electron feels.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Since the outermost electron of alkali metals always feels the same effective nuclear charge (+1), the only factor which affects the first ionisation energy is the distance from the outermost electron to the nucleus.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Since this distance increases down the group, the outermost electron feels less attraction from the nucleus and thus the first ionisation energy decreases.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] This trend is broken in francium due to the relativistic stabilisation and contraction of the 7s orbital, bringing francium's valence electron closer to the nucleus than would be expected from non-relativistic calculations.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] This makes francium's outermost electron feel more attraction from the nucleus, increasing its first ionisation energy slightly beyond that of caesium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The second ionisation energy of the alkali metals is much higher than the first as the second-most loosely held electron is part of a fully filled electron shell and is thus difficult to remove.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The reactivities of the alkali metals increase going down the group.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] This is the result of a combination of two factors: the first ionisation energies and atomisation energies of the alkali metals.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Because the first ionisation energy of the alkali metals decreases down the group, it is easier for the outermost electron to be removed from the atom and participate in chemical reactions, thus increasing reactivity down the group.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Adding the atomisation and first ionisation energies gives a quantity closely related to (but not equal to) the activation energy of the reaction of an alkali metal with another substance.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] This quantity decreases going down the group, and so does the activation energy; thus, chemical reactions can occur faster and the reactivity increases down the group.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Electronegativity is a chemical property that describes the tendency of an atom or a functional group to attract electrons (or electron density) towards itself.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] If the bond between sodium and chlorine in sodium chloride were covalent, the pair of shared electrons would be attracted to the chlorine because the effective nuclear charge on the outer electrons is +7 in chlorine but is only +1 in sodium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The electron pair is attracted so close to the chlorine atom that they are practically transferred to the chlorine atom (an ionic bond).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] However, if the sodium atom was replaced by a lithium atom, the electrons will not be attracted as close to the chlorine atom as before because the lithium atom is smaller, making the electron pair more strongly attracted to the closer effective nuclear charge from lithium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Hence, the larger alkali metal atoms (further down the group) will be less electronegative as the bonding pair is less strongly attracted towards them.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] As mentioned previously, francium is expected to be an exception.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Because of the higher electronegativity of lithium, some of its compounds have a more covalent character.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] For example, lithium iodide (LiI) will dissolve in organic solvents, a property of most covalent compounds.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Lithium fluoride (LiF) is the only alkali halide that is not soluble in water, and lithium hydroxide (LiOH) is the only alkali metal hydroxide that is not deliquescent.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The melting point of a substance is the point where it changes state from solid to liquid while the boiling point of a substance (in liquid state) is the point where the vapour pressure of the liquid equals the environmental pressure surrounding the liquid and all the liquid changes state to gas.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] As a metal is heated to its melting point, the metallic bonds keeping the atoms in place weaken so that the atoms can move around, and the metallic bonds eventually break completely at the metal's boiling point.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Therefore, the falling melting and boiling points of the alkali metals indicate that the strength of the metallic bonds of the alkali metals decreases down the group.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] This is because metal atoms are held together by the electromagnetic attraction from the positive ions to the delocalised electrons.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The increased nuclear charge is not a relevant factor due to the shielding effect.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The alkali metals all have the same crystal structure (body-centred cubic) and thus the only relevant factors are the number of atoms that can fit into a certain volume and the mass of one of the atoms, since density is defined as mass per unit volume.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The first factor depends on the volume of the atom and thus the atomic radius, which increases going down the group; thus, the volume of an alkali metal atom increases going down the group.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The mass of an alkali metal atom also increases going down the group.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Thus, the trend for the densities of the alkali metals depends on their atomic weights and atomic radii; if figures for these two factors are known, the ratios between the densities of the alkali metals can then be calculated.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] The resultant trend is that the densities of the alkali metals increase down the table, with an exception at potassium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Due to having the lowest atomic weight and the largest atomic radius of all the elements in their periods, the alkali metals are the least dense metals in the periodic table.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p01] Lithium, sodium, and potassium are the only three metals in the periodic table that are less dense than water: in fact, lithium is the least dense known solid at room temperature.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metals form complete series of compounds with all usually encountered anions, which well illustrate group trends.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] These compounds can be described as involving the alkali metals losing electrons to acceptor species and forming monopositive ions.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] This description is most accurate for alkali halides and becomes less and less accurate as cationic and anionic charge increase, and as the anion becomes larger and more polarisable.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] For instance, ionic bonding gives way to metallic bonding along the series NaCl, Na2O, Na2S, Na3P, Na3As, Na3Sb, Na3Bi, Na.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] All the alkali metals react vigorously or explosively with cold water, producing an aqueous solution of a strongly basic alkali metal hydroxide and releasing hydrogen gas.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] This reaction becomes more vigorous going down the group: lithium reacts steadily with effervescence, but sodium and potassium can ignite, and rubidium and caesium sink in water and generate hydrogen gas so rapidly that shock waves form in the water that may shatter glass containers.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] When an alkali metal is dropped into water, it produces an explosion, of which there are two separate stages.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The metal reacts with the water first, breaking the hydrogen bonds in the water and producing hydrogen gas; this takes place faster for the more reactive heavier alkali metals.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Second, the heat generated by the first part of the reaction often ignites the hydrogen gas, causing it to burn explosively into the surrounding air.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] This secondary hydrogen gas explosion produces the visible flame above the bowl of water, lake or other body of water, not the initial reaction of the metal with water (which tends to happen mostly under water).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metal hydroxides are the most basic known hydroxides.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Recent research has suggested that the explosive behavior of alkali metals in water is driven by a Coulomb explosion rather than solely by rapid generation of hydrogen itself.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] All alkali metals melt as a part of the reaction with water.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Water molecules ionise the bare metallic surface of the liquid metal, leaving a positively charged metal surface and negatively charged water ions.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The attraction between the charged metal and water ions will rapidly increase the surface area, causing an exponential increase of ionisation.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] When the repulsive forces within the liquid metal surface exceeds the forces of the surface tension, it vigorously explodes.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The hydroxides themselves are the most basic hydroxides known, reacting with acids to give salts and with alcohols to give oligomeric alkoxides.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] They easily react with carbon dioxide to form carbonates or bicarbonates, or with hydrogen sulfide to form sulfides or bisulfides, and may be used to separate thiols from petroleum.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] They react with amphoteric oxides: for example, the oxides of aluminium, zinc, tin, and lead react with the alkali metal hydroxides to give aluminates, zincates, stannates, and plumbates.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Silicon dioxide is acidic, and thus the alkali metal hydroxides can also attack silicate glass.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metals form many intermetallic compounds with each other and the elements from groups 2 to 13 in the periodic table of varying stoichiometries, such as the sodium amalgams with mercury, including Na5Hg8 and Na3Hg.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Some of these have ionic characteristics: taking the alloys with gold, the most electronegative of metals, as an example, NaAu and KAu are metallic, but RbAu and CsAu are semiconductors.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] NaK is an alloy of sodium and potassium that is very useful because it is liquid at room temperature, although precautions must be taken due to its extreme reactivity towards water and air.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] An alloy of 41% caesium, 47% sodium, and 12% potassium has the lowest known melting point of any metal or alloy, −78 °C.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Nevertheless, while the elements in group 14 and beyond tend to form discrete anionic clusters, group 13 elements tend to form polymeric ions with the alkali metal cations located between the giant ionic lattice.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] For example, NaTl consists of a polymeric anion (—Tl−—)n with a covalent diamond cubic structure with Na+ ions located between the anionic lattice.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The larger alkali metals cannot fit similarly into an anionic lattice and tend to force the heavier group 13 elements to form anionic clusters.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Boron is a special case, being the only nonmetal in group 13.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metal borides tend to be boron-rich, involving appreciable boron–boron bonding involving deltahedral structures, and are thermally unstable due to the alkali metals having a very high vapour pressure at elevated temperatures.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] This makes direct synthesis problematic because the alkali metals do not react with boron below 700 °C, and thus this must be accomplished in sealed containers with the alkali metal in excess.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Furthermore, exceptionally in this group, reactivity with boron decreases down the group: lithium reacts completely at 700 °C, but sodium at 900 °C and potassium not until 1200 °C, and the reaction is instantaneous for lithium but takes hours for potassium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Rubidium and caesium borides have not even been characterised.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Various phases are known, such as LiB10, NaB6, NaB15, and KB6.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Under high pressure the boron–boron bonding in the lithium borides changes from following Wade's rules to forming Zintl anions like the rest of group 13.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Lithium and sodium react with carbon to form acetylides, Li2C2 and Na2C2, which can also be obtained by reaction of the metal with acetylene.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] These compounds are over 200 times more electrically conductive than pure graphite, suggesting that the valence electron of the alkali metal is transferred to the graphite layers (e.g.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Upon heating of KC8, the elimination of potassium atoms results in the conversion in sequence to KC24, KC36, KC48 and finally KC60.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] KC8 is a very strong reducing agent and is pyrophoric and explodes on contact with water.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] While the larger alkali metals (K, Rb, and Cs) initially form MC8, the smaller ones initially form MC6, and indeed they require reaction of the metals with graphite at high temperatures around 500 °C to form.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Apart from this, the alkali metals are such strong reducing agents that they can even reduce buckminsterfullerene to produce solid fullerides M*n*C60; sodium, potassium, rubidium, and caesium can form fullerides where *n* = 2, 3, 4, or 6, and rubidium and caesium additionally can achieve *n* = 1.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] When the alkali metals react with the heavier elements in the carbon group (silicon, germanium, tin, and lead), ionic substances with cage-like structures are formed, such as the silicides M4Si4 (M = K, Rb, or Cs), which contains M+ and tetrahedral Si4−4 ions.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The chemistry of alkali metal germanides, involving the germanide ion Ge4− and other cluster (Zintl) ions such as Ge2−4, Ge4−9, Ge2−9, and [(Ge9)2]6−, is largely analogous to that of the corresponding silicides.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Alkali metal stannides are mostly ionic, sometimes with the stannide ion (Sn4−), and sometimes with more complex Zintl ions such as Sn4−9, which appears in tetrapotassium nonastannide (K4Sn9).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The monatomic plumbide ion (Pb4−) is unknown, and indeed its formation is predicted to be energetically unfavourable; alkali metal plumbides have complex Zintl ions, such as Pb4−9.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] These alkali metal germanides, stannides, and plumbides may be produced by reducing germanium, tin, and lead with sodium metal in liquid ammonia.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Lithium, the lightest of the alkali metals, is the only alkali metal which reacts with nitrogen at standard conditions, and its nitride is the only stable alkali metal nitride.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Nitrogen is an unreactive gas because breaking the strong triple bond in the dinitrogen molecule (N2) requires a lot of energy.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The reactions of the other alkali metals with nitrogen would not release enough lattice energy and would thus be endothermic, so they do not form nitrides at standard conditions.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Sodium nitride (Na3N) and potassium nitride (K3N), while existing, are extremely unstable, being prone to decomposing back into their constituent elements, and cannot be produced by reacting the elements with each other at standard conditions.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Steric hindrance forbids the existence of rubidium or caesium nitride.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] However, sodium and potassium form colourless azide salts involving the linear N−3 anion; due to the large size of the alkali metal cations, they are thermally stable enough to be able to melt before decomposing.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] All the alkali metals react readily with phosphorus and arsenic to form phosphides and arsenides with the formula M3Pn (where M represents an alkali metal and Pn represents a pnictogen – phosphorus, arsenic, antimony, or bismuth).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] This is due to the greater size of the P3− and As3− ions, so that less lattice energy needs to be released for the salts to form.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] These are not the only phosphides and arsenides of the alkali metals: for example, potassium has nine different known phosphides, with formulae K3P, K4P3, K5P4, KP, K4P6, K3P7, K3P11, KP10.3, and KP15.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] While most metals form arsenides, only the alkali and alkaline earth metals form mostly ionic arsenides.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The structure of Na3As is complex with unusually short Na–Na distances of 328–330 pm which are shorter than in sodium metal, and this indicates that even with these electropositive metals the bonding cannot be straightforwardly ionic.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Other alkali metal arsenides not conforming to the formula M3As are known, such as LiAs, which has a metallic lustre and electrical conductivity indicating the presence of some metallic bonding.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The antimonides are unstable and reactive as the Sb3− ion is a strong reducing agent; reaction of them with acids form the toxic and unstable gas stibine (SbH3).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Indeed, they have some metallic properties, and the alkali metal antimonides of stoichiometry MSb involve antimony atoms bonded in a spiral Zintl structure.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Bismuthides are not even wholly ionic; they are intermetallic compounds containing partially metallic and partially ionic bonds.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] cluster, composed of three regular octahedra where each octahedron is connected to both of the others by one face each.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] All three octahedra have one edge in common.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] All the alkali metals react vigorously with oxygen at standard conditions.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] They form various types of oxides, such as simple oxides (containing the O2− ion), peroxides (containing the O2−2 ion, where there is a single bond between the two oxygen atoms), superoxides (containing the O−2 ion), and many others.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Lithium burns in air to form lithium oxide, but sodium reacts with oxygen to form a mixture of sodium oxide and sodium peroxide.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Potassium forms a mixture of potassium peroxide and potassium superoxide, while rubidium and caesium form the superoxide exclusively.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Their reactivity increases going down the group: while lithium, sodium and potassium merely burn in air, rubidium and caesium are pyrophoric (spontaneously catch fire in air).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The smaller alkali metals tend to polarise the larger anions (the peroxide and superoxide) due to their small size.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] This attracts the electrons in the more complex anions towards one of its constituent oxygen atoms, forming an oxide ion and an oxygen atom.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] This causes lithium to form the oxide exclusively on reaction with oxygen at room temperature.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] This effect becomes drastically weaker for the larger sodium and potassium, allowing them to form the less stable peroxides.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Rubidium and caesium, at the bottom of the group, are so large that even the least stable superoxides can form.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Because the superoxide releases the most energy when formed, the superoxide is preferentially formed for the larger alkali metals where the more complex anions are not polarised.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The oxides and peroxides for these alkali metals do exist, but do not form upon direct reaction of the metal with oxygen at standard conditions.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] In addition, the small size of the Li+ and O2− ions contributes to their forming a stable ionic lattice structure.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Under controlled conditions, however, all the alkali metals, with the exception of francium, are known to form their oxides, peroxides, and superoxides.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metal peroxides and superoxides are powerful oxidising agents.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] All the stable alkali metals except lithium can form red ozonides (MO3) through low-temperature reaction of the powdered anhydrous hydroxide with ozone: the ozonides may be then extracted using liquid ammonia.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] They slowly decompose at standard conditions to the superoxides and oxygen, and hydrolyse immediately to the hydroxides when in contact with water.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Potassium, rubidium, and caesium also form sesquioxides M2O3, which may be better considered peroxide disuperoxides, [(M+)4(O2−2)(O−2)2].
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Rubidium and caesium can form a great variety of suboxides with the metals in formal oxidation states below +1.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Rubidium can form Rb6O and Rb9O2 (copper-coloured) upon oxidation in air, while caesium forms an immense variety of oxides, such as the ozonide CsO3 and several brightly coloured suboxides, such as Cs7O (bronze), Cs4O (red-violet), Cs11O3 (violet), Cs3O (dark green), CsO, Cs3O2, as well as Cs7O2.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The last of these may be heated under vacuum to generate Cs2O.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metals can also react analogously with the heavier chalcogens (sulfur, selenium, tellurium, and polonium), and all the alkali metal chalcogenides are known (with the exception of francium's).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Reaction with an excess of the chalcogen can similarly result in lower chalcogenides, with chalcogen ions containing chains of the chalcogen atoms in question.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] For example, sodium can react with sulfur to form the sulfide (Na2S) and various polysulfides with the formula Na2S*x* (*x* from 2 to 6), containing the S2− *x* ions.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Due to the basicity of the Se2− and Te2− ions, the alkali metal selenides and tellurides are alkaline in solution; when reacted directly with selenium and tellurium, alkali metal polyselenides and polytellurides are formed along with the selenides and tellurides with the Se2− *x* and Te2− *x* ions.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] They may be obtained directly from the elements in liquid ammonia or when air is not present, and are colourless, water-soluble compounds that air oxidises quickly back to selenium or tellurium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metal polonides are all ionic compounds containing the Po2− ion; they are very chemically stable and can be produced by direct reaction of the elements at around 300–400 °C.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metals are among the most electropositive elements on the periodic table and thus tend to bond ionically to the most electronegative elements on the periodic table, the halogens (fluorine, chlorine, bromine, iodine, and astatine), forming salts known as the alkali metal halides.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The reaction is very vigorous and can sometimes result in explosions.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] All twenty stable alkali metal halides are known; the unstable ones are not known, with the exception of sodium astatide, because of the great instability and rarity of astatine and francium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The most well-known of the twenty is certainly sodium chloride, otherwise known as common salt.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] All of the stable alkali metal halides have the formula MX where M is an alkali metal and X is a halogen.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] They are all white ionic crystalline solids that have high melting points.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] All the alkali metal halides are soluble in water except for lithium fluoride (LiF), which is insoluble in water due to its very high lattice enthalpy.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The high lattice enthalpy of lithium fluoride is due to the small sizes of the Li+ and F− ions, causing the electrostatic interactions between them to be strong: a similar effect occurs for magnesium fluoride, consistent with the diagonal relationship between lithium and magnesium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metals also react similarly with hydrogen to form ionic alkali metal hydrides, where the hydride anion acts as a pseudohalide: these are often used as reducing agents, producing hydrides, complex metal hydrides, or hydrogen gas.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Other pseudohalides are also known, notably the cyanides.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] These are isostructural to the respective halides except for lithium cyanide, indicating that the cyanide ions may rotate freely.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Ternary alkali metal halide oxides, such as Na3ClO, K3BrO (yellow), Na4Br2O, Na4I2O, and K4Br2O, are also known.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The polyhalides are rather unstable, although those of rubidium and caesium are greatly stabilised by the feeble polarising power of these extremely large cations.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] encapsulating a potassium cation (purple).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] At crystalline state, obtained with an X-ray diffraction.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Alkali metal cations do not usually form coordination complexes with simple Lewis bases due to their low charge of just +1 and their relatively large size; thus the Li+ ion forms most complexes and the heavier alkali metal ions form less and less (though exceptions occur for weak complexes).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Lithium in particular has a very rich coordination chemistry in which it exhibits coordination numbers from 1 to 12, although octahedral hexacoordination is its preferred mode.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Because of this, anhydrous salts containing alkali metal cations are often used as desiccants.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Alkali metals also readily form complexes with crown ethers (e.g.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] 12-crown-4 for Li+, 15-crown-5 for Na+, 18-crown-6 for K+, and 21-crown-7 for Rb+) and cryptands due to electrostatic attraction.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The process may be speeded up by a catalyst.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Similar solutions are formed by the heavy divalent alkaline earth metals calcium, strontium, barium, as well as the divalent lanthanides, europium and ytterbium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The amide salt is quite insoluble and readily precipitates out of solution, leaving intensely coloured ammonia solutions of the alkali metals.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Kraus identified the colour as being due to the presence of solvated electrons, which contribute to the high electrical conductivity of these solutions.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] At low concentrations (below 3 M), the solution is dark blue and has ten times the conductivity of aqueous sodium chloride; at higher concentrations (above 3 M), the solution is copper-coloured and has approximately the conductivity of liquid metals like mercury.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] In addition to the alkali metal amide salt and solvated electrons, such ammonia solutions also contain the alkali metal cation (M+), the neutral alkali metal atom (M), diatomic alkali metal molecules (M2) and alkali metal anions (M−).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] These are unstable and eventually become the more thermodynamically stable alkali metal amide and hydrogen gas.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Solvated electrons are powerful reducing agents and are often used in chemical synthesis.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Being the smallest alkali metal, lithium forms the widest variety of and most stable organometallic compounds, which are bonded covalently.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Organolithium compounds are electrically non-conducting volatile solids or liquids that melt at low temperatures, and tend to form oligomers with the structure (RLi)*x* where R is the organic group.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] As the electropositive nature of lithium puts most of the charge density of the bond on the carbon atom, effectively creating a carbanion, organolithium compounds are extremely powerful bases and nucleophiles.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] For use as bases, butyllithiums are often used and are commercially available.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] An example of an organolithium compound is methyllithium ((CH3Li)*x*), which exists in tetrameric (*x* = 4, tetrahedral) and hexameric (*x* = 6, octahedral) forms.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Organolithium compounds, especially *n*-butyllithium, are useful reagents in organic synthesis, as might be expected given lithium's diagonal relationship with magnesium, which plays an important role in the Grignard reaction.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] For example, alkyllithiums and aryllithiums may be used to synthesise aldehydes and ketones by reaction with metal carbonyls.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The reaction with nickel tetracarbonyl, for example, proceeds through an unstable acyl nickel carbonyl complex which then undergoes electrophilic substitution to give the desired aldehyde (using H+ as the electrophile) or ketone (using an alkyl halide) product.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Alkyllithiums and aryllithiums may also react with *N*,*N*-disubstituted amides to give aldehydes and ketones, and symmetrical ketones by reacting with carbon monoxide.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] They thermally decompose to eliminate a β-hydrogen, producing alkenes and lithium hydride: another route is the reaction of ethers with alkyl- and aryllithiums that act as strong bases.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] In non-polar solvents, aryllithiums react as the carbanions they effectively are, turning carbon dioxide to aromatic carboxylic acids (ArCO2H) and aryl ketones to tertiary carbinols (Ar'2C(Ar)OH).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Finally, they may be used to synthesise other organometallic compounds through metal-halogen exchange.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Unlike the organolithium compounds, the organometallic compounds of the heavier alkali metals are predominantly ionic.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The application of organosodium compounds in chemistry is limited in part due to competition from organolithium compounds, which are commercially available and exhibit more convenient reactivity.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The principal organosodium compound of commercial importance is sodium cyclopentadienide.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Sodium tetraphenylborate can also be classified as an organosodium compound since in the solid state sodium is bound to the aryl groups.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Organometallic compounds of the higher alkali metals are even more reactive than organosodium compounds and of limited utility.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] A notable reagent is Schlosser's base, a mixture of *n*-butyllithium and potassium *tert*-butoxide.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] This reagent reacts with propene to form the compound allylpotassium (KCH2CHCH2).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] *cis*-2-Butene and *trans*-2-butene equilibrate when in contact with alkali metals.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Whereas isomerisation is fast with lithium and sodium, it is slow with the heavier alkali metals.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The heavier alkali metals also favour the sterically congested conformation.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Several crystal structures of organopotassium compounds have been reported, establishing that they, like the sodium compounds, are polymeric.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Organosodium, organopotassium, organorubidium and organocaesium compounds are all mostly ionic and are insoluble (or nearly so) in nonpolar solvents.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Alkyl and aryl derivatives of sodium and potassium tend to react with air.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] They cause the cleavage of ethers, generating alkoxides.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] As such, they have to be made by reacting alkylmercury compounds with sodium or potassium metal in inert hydrocarbon solvents.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] While methylsodium forms tetramers like methyllithium, methylpotassium is more ionic and has the nickel arsenide structure with discrete methyl anions and potassium cations.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metals and their hydrides react with acidic hydrocarbons, for example cyclopentadienes and terminal alkynes, to give salts.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Liquid ammonia, ether, or hydrocarbon solvents are used, the most common of which being tetrahydrofuran.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The most important of these compounds is sodium cyclopentadienide, NaC5H5, an important precursor to many transition metal cyclopentadienyl derivatives.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Similarly, the alkali metals react with cyclooctatetraene in tetrahydrofuran to give alkali metal cyclooctatetraenides; for example, dipotassium cyclooctatetraenide (K2C8H8) is an important precursor to many metal cyclooctatetraenyl derivatives, such as uranocene.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The large and very weakly polarising alkali metal cations can stabilise large, aromatic, polarisable radical anions, such as the dark-green sodium naphthalenide, Na+[C10H8•]−, a strong reducing agent.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Upon reacting with oxygen, alkali metals form oxides, peroxides, superoxides and suboxides.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] However, the first three are more common.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The table below shows the types of compounds formed in reaction with oxygen.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The compound in brackets represents the minor product of combustion.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metal peroxides are ionic compounds that are unstable in water.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The peroxide anion is weakly bound to the cation, and it is hydrolysed, forming stronger covalent bonds.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The other oxygen compounds are also unstable in water.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] With sulfur, they form sulfides and polysulfides.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Because alkali metal sulfides are essentially salts of a weak acid and a strong base, they form basic solutions.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Lithium is the only metal that combines directly with nitrogen at room temperature.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Li3N can react with water to liberate ammonia.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] With hydrogen, alkali metals form saline hydrides that hydrolyse in water.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Lithium is the only metal that reacts directly with carbon to give dilithium acetylide.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Na and K can react with acetylene to give acetylides.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] On reaction with water, they generate hydroxide ions and hydrogen gas.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] This reaction is vigorous and highly exothermic and the hydrogen resulted may ignite in air or even explode in the case of Rb and Cs.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metals are very good reducing agents.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] They can reduce metal cations that are less electropositive.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Titanium is produced industrially by the reduction of titanium tetrachloride with Na at 400 °C (van Arkel–de Boer process).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Alkali metals react with halogen derivatives to generate hydrocarbon via the Wurtz reaction.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Alkali metals dissolve in liquid ammonia or other donor solvents like aliphatic amines or hexamethylphosphoramide to give blue solutions.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] These solutions are believed to contain free electrons.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Due to the presence of solvated electrons, these solutions are very powerful reducing agents used in organic synthesis.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Reaction 1) is known as Birch reduction.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Although francium is the heaviest alkali metal that has been discovered, there has been some theoretical work predicting the physical and chemical characteristics of hypothetical heavier alkali metals.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Being the first period 8 element, the undiscovered element ununennium (element 119) is predicted to be the next alkali metal after francium and behave much like their lighter congeners; however, it is also predicted to differ from the lighter alkali metals in some properties.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Its chemistry is predicted to be closer to that of potassium or rubidium instead of caesium or francium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] This is unusual as periodic trends, ignoring relativistic effects would predict ununennium to be even more reactive than caesium and francium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] This lowered reactivity is due to the relativistic stabilisation of ununennium's valence electron, increasing ununennium's first ionisation energy and decreasing the metallic and ionic radii; this effect is already seen for francium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] This assumes that ununennium will behave chemically as an alkali metal, which, although likely, may not be true due to relativistic effects.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The relativistic stabilisation of the 8s orbital also increases ununennium's electron affinity far beyond that of caesium and francium; indeed, ununennium is expected to have an electron affinity higher than all the alkali metals lighter than it.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Relativistic effects also cause a very large drop in the polarisability of ununennium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] On the other hand, ununennium is predicted to continue the trend of melting points decreasing going down the group, being expected to have a melting point between 0 °C and 30 °C.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] On the other hand, the ionic radius of the Uue+ ion is predicted to be larger than that of Rb+, because the 7p orbitals are destabilised and are thus larger than the p-orbitals of the lower shells.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Indeed, many ununennium compounds are expected to have a large covalent character, due to the involvement of the 7p3/2 electrons in the bonding.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Not as much work has been done predicting the properties of the alkali metals beyond ununennium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] This element would be intermediate in properties between an alkali metal and a group 11 element, and while its physical and atomic properties would be closer to the former, its chemistry may be closer to that of the latter.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] However, the 7d electrons of unhexpentium may also be able to participate in chemical reactions along with the 9s electron, possibly allowing oxidation states beyond +1, whence the likely transition metal behaviour of unhexpentium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Due to the alkali and alkaline earth metals both being s-block elements, these predictions for the trends and properties of ununennium and unhexpentium also mostly hold quite similarly for the corresponding alkaline earth metals unbinilium (Ubn) and unhexhexium (Uhh).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] The probable properties of further alkali metals beyond unsepttrium have not been explored yet as of 2019, and they may or may not be able to exist.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] In periods 8 and above of the periodic table, relativistic and shell-structure effects become so strong that extrapolations from lighter congeners become completely inaccurate.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p02] Interest in the chemical properties of ununennium, unhexpentium, and unsepttrium stems from the fact that they are located close to the expected locations of islands of stability, centered at elements 122 (306Ubb) and 164 (482Uhq).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Many other substances are similar to the alkali metals in their tendency to form monopositive cations.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Analogously to the pseudohalogens, they have sometimes been called "pseudo-alkali metals".
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] These substances include some elements and many more polyatomic ions; the polyatomic ions are especially similar to the alkali metals in their large size and weak polarising power.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The element hydrogen, with one electron per neutral atom, is usually placed at the top of Group 1 of the periodic table because of its electron configuration.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] But hydrogen is not normally considered to be an alkali metal.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Metallic hydrogen, which only exists at very high pressures, is known for its electrical and magnetic properties, not its chemical properties.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Under typical conditions, pure hydrogen exists as a diatomic gas consisting of two atoms per molecule (H2); however, the alkali metals form diatomic molecules (such as dilithium, Li2) only at high temperatures, when they are in the gaseous state.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Hydrogen, like the alkali metals, has one valence electron and reacts easily with the halogens, but the similarities mostly end there because of the small size of a bare proton H+ compared to the alkali metal cations.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Its placement above lithium is primarily due to its electron configuration.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] It is sometimes placed above fluorine due to their similar chemical properties, though the resemblance is likewise not absolute.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The first ionisation energy of hydrogen (1312.0 kJ/mol) is much higher than that of the alkali metals.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] As only one additional electron is required to fill in the outermost shell of the hydrogen atom, hydrogen often behaves like a halogen, forming the negative hydride ion, and is very occasionally considered to be a halogen on that basis.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] (The alkali metals can also form negative ions, known as alkalides, but these are little more than laboratory curiosities, being unstable.) An argument against this placement is that formation of hydride from hydrogen is endothermic, unlike the exothermic formation of halides from halogens.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The radius of the H− anion also does not fit the trend of increasing size going down the halogens: indeed, H− is very diffuse because its single proton cannot easily control both electrons.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The electrical resistivity of liquid metallic hydrogen at 3000 K is approximately equal to that of liquid rubidium and caesium at 2000 K at the respective pressures when they undergo a nonmetal-to-metal transition.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The 1s1 electron configuration of hydrogen, while analogous to that of the alkali metals (ns1), is unique because there is no 1p subshell.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Hence it can lose an electron to form the hydron H+, or gain one to form the hydride ion H−.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] In the former case it resembles superficially the alkali metals; in the latter case, the halogens, but the differences due to the lack of a 1p subshell are important enough that neither group fits the properties of hydrogen well.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Group 14 is also a good fit in terms of thermodynamic properties such as ionisation energy and electron affinity, but hydrogen cannot be tetravalent.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Indeed, transferring of protons between chemicals is the basis of acid-base chemistry.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Also unique is hydrogen's ability to form hydrogen bonds, which are an effect of charge-transfer, electrostatic, and electron correlative contributing phenomena.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] While analogous lithium bonds are also known, they are mostly electrostatic.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Nevertheless, hydrogen can take on the same structural role as the alkali metals in some molecular crystals, and has a close relationship with the lightest alkali metals (especially lithium).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The ammonium ion (NH+4) has very similar properties to the heavier alkali metals, acting as an alkali metal intermediate between potassium and rubidium, and is often considered a close relative.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] For example, most alkali metal salts are soluble in water, a property which ammonium salts share.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] It has been estimated that the transition from a mixture of ammonia and dihydrogen molecules to metallic ammonium may occur at pressures just below 25 GPa.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Under standard conditions, ammonium can form a metallic amalgam with mercury.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Other "pseudo-alkali metals" include the alkylammonium cations, in which some of the hydrogen atoms in the ammonium cation are replaced by alkyl or aryl groups.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] In particular, the quaternary ammonium cations (NR+4) are very useful since they are permanently charged, and they are often used as an alternative to the expensive Cs+ to stabilise very large and very easily polarisable anions such as HI−2.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Tetraalkylammonium hydroxides, like alkali metal hydroxides, are very strong bases that react with atmospheric carbon dioxide to form carbonates.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Cobaltocene, Co(C5H5)2, is a metallocene, the cobalt analogue of ferrocene.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Cobaltocene has 19 valence electrons, one more than usually found in organotransition metal complexes, such as its very stable relative, ferrocene, in accordance with the 18-electron rule.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] This additional electron occupies an orbital that is antibonding with respect to the Co–C bonds.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Consequently, many chemical reactions of Co(C5H5)2 are characterized by its tendency to lose this "extra" electron, yielding a very stable 18-electron cation known as cobaltocenium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Many cobaltocenium salts coprecipitate with caesium salts, and cobaltocenium hydroxide is a strong base that absorbs atmospheric carbon dioxide to form cobaltocenium carbonate.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Like the alkali metals, cobaltocene is a strong reducing agent, and decamethylcobaltocene is stronger still due to the combined inductive effect of the ten methyl groups.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Cobalt may be substituted by its heavier congener rhodium to give rhodocene, an even stronger reducing agent.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Iridocene (involving iridium) would presumably be still more potent, but is not very well-studied due to its instability.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Thallium is the heaviest stable element in group 13 of the periodic table.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] It was sometimes considered an alkali metal in continental Europe (but not in England) in the years immediately following its discovery, and was placed just after caesium as the sixth alkali metal in Dmitri Mendeleev's 1869 periodic table and Julius Lothar Meyer's 1868 periodic table.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Mendeleev's 1871 periodic table and Meyer's 1870 periodic table put thallium in its current position in the boron group and left the space below caesium blank.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] However, thallium also displays the oxidation state +3, which no known alkali metal displays (although ununennium, the undiscovered seventh alkali metal, is predicted to possibly display the +3 oxidation state).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The sixth alkali metal is now considered to be francium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] While Tl+ is stabilised by the inert-pair effect, this inert pair of 6s electrons is still able to participate chemically, so that these electrons are stereochemically active in aqueous solution.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Additionally, the thallium halides (except TlF) are quite insoluble in water, and TlI has an unusual structure because of the presence of the stereochemically active inert pair in thallium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The group 11 metals (or coinage metals), copper, silver, and gold, are typically categorised as transition metals given they can form ions with incomplete d-shells.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Physically, they have the relatively low melting points and high electronegativity values associated with post-transition metals.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] "The filled *d* subshell and free *s* electron of Cu, Ag, and Au contribute to their high electrical and thermal conductivity.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] They are occasionally classified as post-transition metals.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Their spectra are analogous to those of the alkali metals.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Their monopositive ions are paramagnetic and contribute no colour to their salts, like those of the alkali metals.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] In Mendeleev's 1871 periodic table, copper, silver, and gold are listed twice, once under group VIII (with the iron triad and platinum group metals), and once under group IB.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Group IB was nonetheless parenthesised to note that it was tentative.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Mendeleev's main criterion for group assignment was the maximum oxidation state of an element: on that basis, the group 11 elements could not be classified in group IB, due to the existence of copper(II) and gold(III) compounds being known at that time.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] However, eliminating group IB would make group I the only main group (group VIII was labelled a transition group) to lack an A–B bifurcation.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The coinage metals were traditionally regarded as a subdivision of the alkali metal group, due to them sharing the characteristic s1 electron configuration of the alkali metals (group 1: p6s1; group 11: d10s1).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] However, the similarities are largely confined to the stoichiometries of the +1 compounds of both groups, and not their chemical properties.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] This stems from the filled d subshell providing a much weaker shielding effect on the outermost s electron than the filled p subshell, so that the coinage metals have much higher first ionisation energies and smaller ionic radii than do the corresponding alkali metals.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Furthermore, they have higher melting points, hardnesses, and densities, and lower reactivities and solubilities in liquid ammonia, as well as having more covalent character in their compounds.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Finally, the alkali metals are at the top of the electrochemical series, whereas the coinage metals are almost at the very bottom.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The production of pure alkali metals is somewhat complicated due to their extreme reactivity with commonly used substances, such as water.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The remaining insoluble alkali metal carbonate is then precipitated selectively; the salt is then dissolved in hydrochloric acid to produce the chloride.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The result is then left to evaporate and the alkali metal can then be isolated.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium and sodium are typically isolated through electrolysis from their liquid chlorides, with calcium chloride typically added to lower the melting point of the mixture.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The heavier alkali metals, however, are more typically isolated in a different way, where a reducing agent (typically sodium for potassium and magnesium or calcium for the heaviest alkali metals) is used to reduce the alkali metal chloride.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The liquid or gaseous product (the alkali metal) then undergoes fractional distillation for purification.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Most routes to the pure alkali metals require the use of electrolysis due to their high reactivity; one of the few which does not is the pyrolysis of the corresponding alkali metal azide, which yields the metal for sodium, potassium, rubidium, and caesium and the nitride for lithium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium salts have to be extracted from the water of mineral springs, brine pools, and brine deposits.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The metal is produced electrolytically from a mixture of fused lithium chloride and potassium chloride.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Sodium occurs mostly in seawater and dried seabed, but is now produced through electrolysis of sodium chloride by lowering the melting point of the substance to below 700 °C through the use of a Downs cell.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Extremely pure sodium can be produced through the thermal decomposition of sodium azide.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Potassium occurs in many minerals, such as sylvite (potassium chloride).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Previously, potassium was generally made from the electrolysis of potassium chloride or potassium hydroxide, found extensively in places such as Canada, Russia, Belarus, Germany, Israel, United States, and Jordan, in a method similar to how sodium was produced in the late 1800s and early 1900s.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] However, these methods are problematic because the potassium metal tends to dissolve in its molten chloride and vaporises significantly at the operating temperatures, potentially forming the explosive superoxide.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] As a result, pure potassium metal is now produced by reducing molten potassium chloride with sodium metal at 850 °C.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Although sodium is less reactive than potassium, this process works because at such high temperatures potassium is more volatile than sodium and can easily be distilled off, so that the equilibrium shifts towards the right to produce more potassium gas and proceeds almost to completion.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Metals like sodium are obtained by electrolysis of molten salts.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Rb & Cs obtained mainly as by products of Li processing.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] To make pure caesium, ores of caesium and rubidium are crushed and heated to 650 °C with sodium metal, generating an alloy that can then be separated via a fractional distillation technique.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Because metallic caesium is too reactive to handle, it is normally offered as caesium azide (CsN3).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Caesium hydroxide is formed when caesium interacts aggressively with water and ice (CsOH).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Rubidium is the 16th most abundant element in the earth's crust; however, it is quite rare.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Some minerals found in North America, South Africa, Russia, and Canada contain rubidium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Some potassium minerals (lepidolites, biotites, feldspar, carnallite) contain it, together with caesium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Pollucite, carnallite, leucite, and lepidolite are all minerals that contain rubidium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] As a by-product of lithium extraction, it is commercially obtained from lepidolite.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Rubidium is also found in potassium rocks and brines, which is a commercial supply.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The majority of rubidium is now obtained as a byproduct of refining lithium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Rubidium is used in vacuum tubes as a getter, a material that combines with and removes trace gases from vacuum tubes.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] For several years in the 1950s and 1960s, a by-product of the potassium production called Alkarb was a main source for rubidium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Alkarb contained 21% rubidium while the rest was potassium and a small fraction of caesium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Today the largest producers of caesium, for example the Tanco Mine in Manitoba, Canada, produce rubidium as by-product from pollucite.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Today, a common method for separating rubidium from potassium and caesium is the fractional crystallisation of a rubidium and caesium alum (Cs, Rb)Al(SO4)2·12H2O, which yields pure rubidium alum after approximately 30 recrystallisations.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The limited applications and the lack of a mineral rich in rubidium limit the production of rubidium compounds to 2 to 4 tonnes per year.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Caesium, however, is not produced from the above reaction.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Instead, the mining of pollucite ore is the main method of obtaining pure caesium, extracted from the ore mainly by three methods: acid digestion, alkaline decomposition, and direct reduction.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Both metals are produced as by-products of lithium production: after 1958, when interest in lithium's thermonuclear properties increased sharply, the production of rubidium and caesium also increased correspondingly.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Pure rubidium and caesium metals are produced by reducing their chlorides with calcium metal at 750 °C and low pressure.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] As a result of its extreme rarity in nature, most francium is synthesised in the nuclear reaction 197Au + 18O → 210Fr + 5 n, yielding francium-209, francium-210, and francium-211.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The greatest quantity of francium ever assembled to date is about 300,000 neutral atoms, which were synthesised using the nuclear reaction given above.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] When the only natural isotope francium-223 is specifically required, it is produced as the alpha daughter of actinium-227, itself produced synthetically from the neutron irradiation of natural radium-226, one of the daughters of natural uranium-238.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium, sodium, and potassium have many useful applications, while rubidium and caesium are very notable in academic contexts but do not have many applications yet.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium is the key ingredient for a range of lithium-based batteries, and lithium oxide can help process silica.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium stearate is a thickener and can be used to make lubricating greases; it is produced from lithium hydroxide, which is also used to absorb carbon dioxide in space capsules and submarines.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium chloride is used as a brazing alloy for aluminium parts.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] In medicine, some lithium salts are used as mood-stabilising pharmaceuticals.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Metallic lithium is used in alloys with magnesium and aluminium to give very tough and light alloys.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Sodium compounds have many applications, the most well-known being sodium chloride as table salt.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Sodium salts of fatty acids are used as soap.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Pure sodium metal also has many applications, including use in sodium-vapour lamps, which produce very efficient light compared to other types of lighting, and can help smooth the surface of other metals.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Being a strong reducing agent, it is often used to reduce many other metals, such as titanium and zirconium, from their chlorides.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Furthermore, it is very useful as a heat-exchange liquid in fast breeder nuclear reactors due to its low melting point, viscosity, and cross-section towards neutron absorption.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Sodium-ion batteries may provide cheaper alternatives to their equivalent lithium-based cells.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Both sodium and potassium are commonly used as GRAS counterions to create more water-soluble and hence more bioavailable salt forms of acidic pharmaceuticals.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Potassium compounds are often used as fertilisers as potassium is an important element for plant nutrition.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Potassium hydroxide is a very strong base, and is used to control the pH of various substances.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Potassium nitrate and potassium permanganate are often used as powerful oxidising agents.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Potassium superoxide is used in breathing masks, as it reacts with carbon dioxide to give potassium carbonate and oxygen gas.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Pure potassium metal is not often used, but its alloys with sodium may substitute for pure sodium in fast breeder nuclear reactors.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Rubidium and caesium are often used in atomic clocks.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Caesium atomic clocks are extraordinarily accurate; if a clock had been made at the time of the dinosaurs, it would be off by less than four seconds (after 80 million years).
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] For that reason, caesium atoms are used as the definition of the second.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Rubidium ions are often used in purple fireworks, and caesium is often used in drilling fluids in the petroleum industry.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Francium has no commercial applications, but because of francium's relatively simple atomic structure, among other things, it has been used in spectroscopy experiments, leading to more information regarding energy levels and the coupling constants of the weak interaction.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Studies on the light emitted by laser-trapped francium-210 ions have provided accurate data on transitions between atomic energy levels, similar to those predicted by quantum theory.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Pure alkali metals are dangerously reactive with air and water and must be kept away from heat, fire, oxidising agents, acids, most organic compounds, halocarbons, plastics, and moisture.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] They also react with carbon dioxide and carbon tetrachloride, so that normal fire extinguishers are counterproductive when used on alkali metal fires.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Some Class D dry powder extinguishers designed for metal fires are effective, depriving the fire of oxygen and cooling the alkali metal.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Experiments are usually conducted using only small quantities of a few grams in a fume hood.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Small quantities of lithium may be disposed of by reaction with cool water, but the heavier alkali metals should be dissolved in the less reactive isopropanol.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The alkali metals must be stored under mineral oil or an inert atmosphere.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The inert atmosphere used may be argon or nitrogen gas, except for lithium, which reacts with nitrogen.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The bioinorganic chemistry of the alkali metal ions has been extensively reviewed.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Solid state crystal structures have been determined for many complexes of alkali metal ions in small peptides, nucleic acid constituents, carbohydrates and ionophore complexes.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium naturally only occurs in traces in biological systems and has no known biological role, but does have effects on the body when ingested.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium carbonate is used as a mood stabiliser in psychiatry to treat bipolar disorder (manic-depression) in daily doses of about 0.5 to 2 grams, although there are side-effects.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Excessive ingestion of lithium causes drowsiness, slurred speech and vomiting, among other symptoms, and poisons the central nervous system, which is dangerous as the required dosage of lithium to treat bipolar disorder is only slightly lower than the toxic dosage.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Its biochemistry, the way it is handled by the human body and studies using rats and goats suggest that it is an essential trace element, although the natural biological function of lithium in humans has yet to be identified.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Sodium and potassium occur in all known biological systems, generally functioning as electrolytes inside and outside cells.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Sodium is an essential nutrient that regulates blood volume, blood pressure, osmotic equilibrium and pH; the minimum physiological requirement for sodium is 500 milligrams per day.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Sodium chloride (also known as common salt) is the principal source of sodium in the diet, and is used as seasoning and preservative, such as for pickling and jerky; most of it comes from processed foods.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The Dietary Reference Intake for sodium is 1.5 grams per day, but most people in the United States consume more than 2.3 grams per day, the minimum amount that promotes hypertension; this in turn causes 7.6 million premature deaths worldwide.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Potassium is the major cation (positive ion) inside animal cells, while sodium is the major cation outside animal cells.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The concentration differences of these charged particles causes a difference in electric potential between the inside and outside of cells, known as the membrane potential.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The balance between potassium and sodium is maintained by ion transporter proteins in the cell membrane.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The cell membrane potential created by potassium and sodium ions allows the cell to generate an action potential—a "spike" of electrical discharge.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The ability of cells to produce electrical discharge is critical for body functions such as neurotransmission, muscle contraction, and heart function.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Disruption of this balance may thus be fatal: for example, ingestion of large amounts of potassium compounds can lead to hyperkalemia strongly influencing the cardiovascular system.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Potassium chloride is used in the United States for lethal injection executions.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Due to their similar atomic radii, rubidium and caesium in the body mimic potassium and are taken up similarly.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Rubidium has no known biological role, but may help stimulate metabolism, and, similarly to caesium, replace potassium in the body causing potassium deficiency.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Partial substitution is quite possible and rather non-toxic: a 70 kg person contains on average 0.36 g of rubidium, and an increase in this value by 50 to 100 times did not show negative effects in test persons.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Rats can survive up to 50% substitution of potassium by rubidium.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Rubidium (and to a much lesser extent caesium) can function as temporary cures for hypokalemia; while rubidium can adequately physiologically substitute potassium in some systems, caesium is never able to do so.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] There is only very limited evidence in the form of deficiency symptoms for rubidium being possibly essential in goats; even if this is true, the trace amounts usually present in food are more than enough.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Caesium compounds are rarely encountered by most people, but most caesium compounds are mildly toxic.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Like rubidium, caesium tends to substitute potassium in the body, but is significantly larger and is therefore a poorer substitute.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Excess caesium can lead to hypokalemia, arrhythmia, and acute cardiac arrest, but such amounts would not ordinarily be encountered in natural sources.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] As such, caesium is not a major chemical environmental pollutant.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] The median lethal dose (LD50) value for caesium chloride in mice is 2.3 g per kilogram, which is comparable to the LD50 values of potassium chloride and sodium chloride.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Caesium chloride has been promoted as an alternative cancer therapy, but has been linked to the deaths of over 50 patients, on whom it was used as part of a scientifically unvalidated cancer treatment.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Radioisotopes of caesium require special precautions: the improper handling of caesium-137 gamma ray sources can lead to release of this radioisotope and radiation injuries.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Perhaps the best-known case is the Goiânia accident of 1987, in which an improperly-disposed-of radiation therapy system from an abandoned clinic in the city of Goiânia, Brazil, was scavenged from a junkyard, and the glowing caesium salt sold to curious, uneducated buyers.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] This led to four deaths and serious injuries from radiation exposure.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Together with caesium-134, iodine-131, and strontium-90, caesium-137 was among the isotopes distributed by the Chernobyl disaster which constitute the greatest risk to health.
[src:carbide/alkali-metal-p03] Radioisotopes of francium would presumably be dangerous as well due to their high decay energy and short half-life, but none have been produced in large enough amounts to pose any serious risk.
[src:carbide/alkalide] An **alkalide** is a chemical compound in which alkali metal atoms are anions (negative ions) with a charge or oxidation state of −1.
[src:carbide/alkalide] Until the first discovery of alkalides in the 1970s, alkali metals were known to appear in salts only as cations (positive ions) with a charge or oxidation state of +1.
[src:carbide/alkalide] These types of compounds are of theoretical interest due to their unusual stoichiometry and low ionization potentials.
[src:carbide/alkalide] Alkalide compounds are chemically related to the electrides, salts in which trapped electrons are effectively the anions.
[src:carbide/alkalide] Alkali metals form many well-known stable salts.
[src:carbide/alkalide] Sodium chloride (common table salt), Na+Cl−, illustrates the usual role of an alkali metal such as sodium.
[src:carbide/alkalide] In the empirical formula for this ionic compound, the positively charged sodium ion is balanced by a negatively charged chloride ion.
[src:carbide/alkalide] The traditional explanation for stable Na+ is that the loss of one electron from elemental sodium to produce a cation with charge of +1 produces a stable closed-shell electron configuration.
[src:carbide/alkalide] Normally, alkalides are thermally labile due to the high reactivity of the alkalide anion, which is theoretically able to break most covalent bonds including the carbon–oxygen bonds in a typical cryptand.
[src:carbide/alkalide] The introduction of a special cryptand ligand containing amines instead of ether linkages has allowed the isolation of kalides and natrides that are stable at room temperature.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The **alkaline earth metals** are six chemical elements in group 2 of the periodic table.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] They are beryllium (Be), magnesium (Mg), calcium (Ca), strontium (Sr), barium (Ba), and radium (Ra).
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The elements have very similar properties: they are all shiny, silvery-white, somewhat reactive metals at standard temperature and pressure.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Together with helium, these elements have in common an outer s orbital which is full—that is, this orbital contains its full complement of two electrons, which the alkaline earth metals readily lose to form cations with charge +2, and an oxidation state of +2.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Helium is grouped with the noble gases and not with the alkaline earth metals, but it is theorized to have some similarities to beryllium when forced into bonding and has sometimes been suggested to belong to group 2.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] All the discovered alkaline earth metals occur in nature, although radium occurs only through the decay chain of uranium and thorium and not as a primordial element.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] There have been experiments, all unsuccessful, to try to synthesize element 120, the next potential member of the group.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The chemistry of radium is not well-established due to its radioactivity; thus, the presentation of its properties here is limited.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The alkaline earth metals are all silver-colored and soft, and have relatively low densities, melting points, and boiling points.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] In chemical terms, all of the alkaline earth metals react with the halogens to form the alkaline earth metal halides, all of which are ionic crystalline compounds (except for beryllium chloride, beryllium bromide and beryllium iodide, which are covalent).
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] All the alkaline earth metals except beryllium also react with water to form strongly alkaline hydroxides and, thus, should be handled with great care.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The heavier alkaline earth metals react more vigorously than the lighter ones.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The alkaline earth metals have the second-lowest first ionization energies in their respective periods of the periodic table because of their somewhat low effective nuclear charges and the ability to attain a full outer shell configuration by losing just two electrons.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The second ionization energy of all of the alkaline metals is also somewhat low.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium is an exception: It does not react with water or steam unless at very high temperatures, and its halides are covalent.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] If beryllium did form compounds with an ionization state of +2, it would polarize electron clouds that are near it very strongly and would cause extensive orbital overlap, since beryllium has a high charge density.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] All compounds that include beryllium have a covalent bond.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Even the compound beryllium fluoride, which is the most ionic beryllium compound, has a low melting point and a low electrical conductivity when melted.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] All the alkaline earth metals have two electrons in their valence shell, so the energetically preferred state of achieving a filled electron shell is to lose two electrons to form doubly charged positive ions.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The alkaline earth metals all react with the halogens to form ionic halides, such as calcium chloride (CaCl 2), as well as reacting with oxygen to form oxides such as strontium oxide (SrO).
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium, strontium, and barium react with water to produce hydrogen gas and their respective hydroxides (magnesium also reacts, but much more slowly), and also undergo transmetalation reactions to exchange ligands.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Isotopes of all six alkaline earth metals are present in the Earth's crust and the Solar System at varying concentrations, dependent upon the nuclides' half-lives and, hence, their nuclear stabilities.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The four underlined isotopes in the list are predicted by radionuclide decay energetics to be only observationally stable and to decay with extremely long half-lives through double-beta decay, though no decays attributed definitively to these isotopes have yet been observed as of 2024.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Radium has no stable nor primordial isotopes.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] In addition to the stable species, calcium and barium each have one extremely long-lived and primordial radionuclide: calcium-48 and barium-130, with half-lives of 5.6×1019 and 1.6×1021 years, respectively.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Both are far longer than the current age of the universe (4.7× and 117× billion times longer, respectively) and less than one part per ten billion has decayed since the formation of the Earth.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The two isotopes are stable for practical purposes.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Apart from the 21 stable or nearly-stable isotopes, the six alkaline earth elements each possess a large number of known radioisotopes.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium-7, beryllium-10, and calcium-41 are trace, as well as cosmogenic, nuclides, formed by the impact of cosmic rays with atmospheric or crustal atoms.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The longest half-lives among them are 1.387 million years for beryllium-10, 99.4 thousand years for calcium-41, 1599 years for radium-226 (radium's longest-lived isotope), 28.90 years for strontium-90, 10.51 years for barium-133, and 5.75 years for radium-228.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] All others have half-lives of less than half a year, most significantly shorter.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium-48 and barium-130, the two primordial and non-stable isotopes, decay only through double beta emission and have extremely long half-lives, by virtue of the extremely low probability of both beta decays occurring at the same time.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] All isotopes of radium are highly radioactive and are primarily generated through the decay of heavier radionuclides.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The longest-lived of them is radium-226, a member of the decay chain of uranium-238.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium-90 and barium-140 are common fission products of uranium in nuclear reactors, accounting for 5.73% and 6.31% of uranium-235's fission products respectively when bombarded by thermal neutrons.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The two isotopes have half-lives each of 28.90 years and 12.7 days.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium-90 is produced in appreciable quantities in operating nuclear reactors running on uranium-235 or plutonium-239 fuel, and a minuscule secular equilibrium concentration is also present due to rare spontaneous fission decays in naturally occurring uranium.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium-48 is the lightest nuclide known to undergo double beta decay.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Naturally occurring calcium and barium are very weakly radioactive: calcium contains about 0.1874% calcium-48, and barium contains about 0.1062% barium-130.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] On average, one double-beta decay of calcium-48 will occur per second for every 90 tons of natural calcium, or 230 tons of limestone (calcium carbonate).
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Through the same decay mechanism, one decay of barium-130 will occur per second for every 16,000 tons of natural barium, or 27,000 tons of baryte (barium sulfate).
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The longest-lived isotope of radium is radium-226 with a half-life of 1600 years; it, along with radium-223, -224, and -228, occurs naturally in the decay chains of primordial thorium and uranium.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium-8 is notable by its absence as it splits in half virtually instantaneously into two alpha particles whenever it is formed.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The triple alpha process in stars can only occur at energies high enough for beryllium-8 to fuse with a third alpha particle before it can decay, forming carbon-12.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] This thermonuclear rate-limiting bottleneck is the reason most main sequence stars spend billions of years fusing hydrogen within their cores, and only rarely manage to fuse carbon before collapsing into a stellar remnant, and even then merely for a timescale of ~1000 years.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The radioisotopes of alkaline earth metals tend to be "bone seekers" as they behave chemically similar to calcium, an integral component of hydroxyapatite in compact bone, and gradually accumulate in the human skeleton.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The incorporated radionuclides inflict significant damage to the bone marrow over time through the emission of ionizing radiation, primarily alpha particles.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] This property is made use of in a positive manner in the radiotherapy of certain bone cancers, since the radionuclides' chemical properties causes them to preferentially target cancerous growths in bone matter, leaving the rest of the body relatively unharmed.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Compared to their neighbors in the periodic table, alkaline earth metals tend to have a larger number of stable isotopes as they all possess an even number of protons, owing to their status as group 2 elements.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Their isotopes are generally more stable due to nucleon pairing.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] This stability is further enhanced if the isotope also has an even number of neutrons, as both kinds of nucleons can then participate in pairing and contribute to nuclei stability.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The alkaline earth metals are named after their oxides, the *alkaline earths*, whose old-fashioned names were beryllia, magnesia, lime, strontia, and baria.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] These oxides are basic (alkaline) when combined with water.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] "Earth" was a term applied by early chemists to nonmetallic substances that are insoluble in water and resistant to heating—properties shared by these oxides.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The realization that these earths were not elements but compounds is attributed to the chemist Antoine Lavoisier.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] In his *Traité Élémentaire de Chimie* (*Elements of Chemistry*) of 1789 he called them salt-forming earth elements.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Later, he suggested that the alkaline earths might be metal oxides, but admitted that this was mere conjecture.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] In 1808, acting on Lavoisier's idea, Humphry Davy became the first to obtain samples of the metals by electrolysis of their molten earths, thus supporting Lavoisier's hypothesis and causing the group to be named the *alkaline earth metals*.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The calcium compounds calcite and lime have been known and used since prehistoric times.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The same is true for the beryllium compounds beryl and emerald.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The other compounds of the alkaline earth metals were discovered starting in the early 15th century.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The magnesium compound magnesium sulfate was first discovered in 1618 by a farmer at Epsom in England.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium carbonate was discovered in minerals in the Scottish village of Strontian in 1790.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The last element is the least abundant: radioactive radium, which was extracted from uraninite in 1898.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] All elements except beryllium were isolated by electrolysis of molten compounds.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium, calcium, and strontium were first produced by Humphry Davy in 1808, whereas beryllium was independently isolated by Friedrich Wöhler and Antoine Bussy in 1828 by reacting beryllium compounds with potassium.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] In 1910, radium was isolated as a pure metal by Curie and André-Louis Debierne also by electrolysis.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryl, a mineral that contains beryllium, has been known since the time of the Ptolemaic Kingdom in Egypt.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Although it was originally thought that beryl was an aluminum silicate, beryl was later found to contain a then-unknown element when, in 1797, Louis-Nicolas Vauquelin dissolved aluminum hydroxide from beryl in an alkali.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] In 1828, Friedrich Wöhler and Antoine Bussy independently isolated this new element, beryllium, by the same method, which involved a reaction of beryllium chloride with metallic potassium; this reaction was not able to produce large ingots of beryllium.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] It was not until 1898, when Paul Lebeau performed an electrolysis of a mixture of beryllium fluoride and sodium fluoride, that large pure samples of beryllium were produced.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium was first produced by Humphry Davy in England in 1808 using electrolysis of a mixture of magnesia and mercuric oxide.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Antoine Bussy prepared it in coherent form in 1831.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Davy's first suggestion for a name was magnium, but the name magnesium is now used.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Lime has been used as a material for building since 7000 to 14,000 BCE, and kilns used for lime have been dated to 2,500 BCE in Khafaja, Mesopotamia.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium as a material has been known since at least the first century, as the ancient Romans were known to have used calcium oxide by preparing it from lime.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium sulfate has been known to be able to set broken bones since the tenth century.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium itself, however, was not isolated until 1808, when Humphry Davy, in England, used electrolysis on a mixture of lime and mercuric oxide, after hearing that Jöns Jakob Berzelius had prepared a calcium amalgam from the electrolysis of lime in mercury.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] In 1790, physician Adair Crawford discovered ores with distinctive properties, which were named *strontites* in 1793 by Thomas Charles Hope, a chemistry professor at the University of Glasgow, who confirmed Crawford's discovery.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium was eventually isolated in 1808 by Humphry Davy by electrolysis of a mixture of strontium chloride and mercuric oxide.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The discovery was announced by Davy on 30 June 1808 at a lecture to the Royal Society.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Barite, a mineral containing barium, was first recognized as containing a new element in 1774 by Carl Scheele, although he was able to isolate only barium oxide.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Barium oxide was isolated again two years later by Johan Gottlieb Gahn.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Later in the 18th century, William Withering noticed a heavy mineral in the Cumberland lead mines, which are now known to contain barium.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Barium itself was finally isolated in 1808 when Humphry Davy used electrolysis with molten salts, and Davy named the element *barium*, after baryta.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Later, Robert Bunsen and Augustus Matthiessen isolated pure barium by electrolysis of a mixture of barium chloride and ammonium chloride.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] While studying uraninite, on 21 December 1898, Marie and Pierre Curie discovered that, even after uranium had decayed, the material created was still radioactive.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The material behaved somewhat similarly to barium compounds, although some properties, such as the color of the flame test and spectral lines, were much different.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] They announced the discovery of a new element on 26 December 1898 to the French Academy of Sciences.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Radium was named in 1899 from the word *radius*, meaning *ray*, as radium emitted power in the form of rays.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium occurs in the Earth's crust at a concentration of two to six parts per million (ppm), much of which is in soils, where it has a concentration of six ppm.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium is one of the rarest elements in seawater, even rarer than elements such as scandium, with a concentration of 0.2 parts per trillion.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] However, in freshwater, beryllium is somewhat more common, with a concentration of 0.1 parts per billion.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium and calcium are very common in the Earth's crust, being respectively the fifth and eighth most abundant elements.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] None of the alkaline earth metals are found in their elemental state.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Common magnesium-containing minerals are carnallite, magnesite, and dolomite.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Common calcium-containing minerals are chalk, limestone, gypsum, and anhydrite.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium is the 15th most abundant element in the Earth's crust.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The principal minerals are celestite and strontianite.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Barium is slightly less common, much of it in the mineral barite.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Radium, being a decay product of uranium, is found in all uranium-bearing ores.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Due to its relatively short half-life, radium from the Earth's early history has decayed, and present-day samples have all come from the much slower decay of uranium.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Production of the six alkaline earth metals can occur in many ways.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Most beryllium is extracted from beryllium hydroxide.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] One production method is sintering, done by mixing beryl, sodium fluorosilicate, and soda at high temperatures to form sodium fluoroberyllate, aluminum oxide, and silicon dioxide.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] A solution of sodium fluoroberyllate and sodium hydroxide in water is then used to form beryllium hydroxide by precipitation.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Alternatively, in the melt method, powdered beryl is heated to high temperature, cooled with water, then heated again slightly in sulfuric acid, eventually yielding beryllium hydroxide.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The beryllium hydroxide from either method then produces beryllium fluoride and beryllium chloride through a somewhat long process.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Electrolysis or heating of these compounds can then produce beryllium.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] In general, strontium carbonate is extracted from the mineral celestite through two methods: by leaching the celestite with sodium carbonate, or in a more complicated way involving coal.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] To produce barium, barite (impure barium sulfate) is converted to barium sulfide by carbothermic reduction (such as with coke).
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The sulfide is water-soluble and easily reacted to form pure barium sulfate, used for commercial pigments, or other compounds, such as barium nitrate.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] These in turn are calcined into barium oxide, which eventually yields pure barium after reduction with aluminum.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The most important supplier of barium is China, which produces more than 50% of world supply.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium is usually produced from magnesite ore, as well as dolomite.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] When dolomite is crushed, roasted and mixed with seawater in large tanks, magnesium hydroxide settles to the bottom.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Heating, mixing in coke, and reacting with chlorine, then produces molten magnesium chloride.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] This can be electrolyzed, releasing magnesium, which floats to the surface.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium is the fifth most abundant element in the Earth's crust, existing mostly as calcium carbonate.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Other important minerals of calcium include gypsum, anhydrite, fluorite, and apatite.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The largest producers of calcium in the world are China and Russia, where Davy's method of electrolysis is used on calcium chloride to produce the metal.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Other large producers of calcium are the U.S. and Canada, where lime is reduced with aluminium at high temperatures.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Marie Skłodowska-Curie developed the first methods of radium extraction using residues of pitchblende, following her extraction of uranium.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] These residues contained mostly barium sulfate.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Curie's method was used until 1940, after which mixed bromides became more popular.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] As of 2011, radium is extracted only from spent reactor fuel as oxides.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The pure metal can be isolated by reduction with aluminium in a vacuum at 1,200 °C.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium is used mainly in military applications, but non-military uses exist.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] In electronics, beryllium is used as a p-type dopant in some semiconductors, and beryllium oxide is used as a high-strength electrical insulator and heat conductor.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium alloys are used for mechanical parts when stiffness, light weight, and dimensional stability are required over a wide temperature range.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium-9 is used in small-scale neutron sources that use the reaction 9Be + 4He (α) → 12C + 1n, the reaction used by James Chadwick when he discovered the neutron.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Its low atomic weight and low neutron absorption cross-section would make beryllium suitable as a neutron moderator, but its high price and the readily available alternatives such as water, heavy water and nuclear graphite have limited this to niche applications.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] In the FLiBe eutectic used in molten salt reactors, beryllium's role as a moderator is more incidental than the desired property leading to its use.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] It offers advantages over other structural materials such as aluminum, but magnesium's usage is hindered by its flammability.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium is often alloyed with aluminum, zinc and manganese to increase its strength and corrosion resistance.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium has many other industrial applications, such as its role in the production of iron and steel, and in the Kroll process for production of titanium.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium is used as a reducing agent in the separation of other metals such as uranium from ore.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] It is a major component of many alloys, especially aluminum and copper alloys, and is also used to deoxidize alloys.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium has roles in the making of cheese, mortars, and cement.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium and barium have fewer applications than the lighter alkaline earth metals.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium carbonate is used in the manufacturing of red fireworks.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Pure strontium is used in the study of neurotransmitter release in neurons.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Radioactive strontium-90 finds some use in RTGs, which utilize its decay heat.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Barium is used in vacuum tubes as a getter to remove gases.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Barium sulfate has many uses in the petroleum industry, and other industries.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Radium has many former applications based on its radioactivity, but its use is no longer common because of the adverse health effects and long half-life.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Radium was frequently used in luminous paints, although this use was stopped after it sickened workers.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The nuclear quackery that alleged health benefits of radium formerly led to its addition to drinking water, toothpaste, and many other products.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Radium is no longer used even when its radioactive properties are desired because its long half-life makes safe disposal challenging.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] For example, in brachytherapy, shorter-lived alternatives such as iridium-192 are usually used instead.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Anhydrous calcium chloride is a hygroscopic substance that is used as a desiccant.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Exposed to air, it will absorb water vapour from the air, forming a solution.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] This property is known as deliquescence.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] With carbon, they form acetylides directly.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Alkaline earth metals react with hydrogen to generate saline hydride that are unstable in water.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Ca, Sr, and Ba readily react with water to form hydroxide and hydrogen gas.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Be and Mg are passivated by an impervious layer of oxide.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] However, amalgamated magnesium will react with water vapor.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Alkaline earth metals reduce the nonmetal from its oxide.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] It dissolves in concentrated sodium hydroxide.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium reacts with alkyl halides via an insertion reaction to generate Grignard reagents.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The table below presents the colors observed when the flame of a Bunsen burner is exposed to salts of alkaline earth metals.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Be and Mg do not impart colour to the flame due to their small size.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Disodium phosphate is a very selective reagent for magnesium ions and, in the presence of ammonium salts and ammonia, forms a white precipitate of ammonium magnesium phosphate.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Ca2+ forms a white precipitate with ammonium oxalate.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium oxalate is insoluble in water, but is soluble in mineral acids.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium ions precipitate with soluble sulfate salts.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] All ions of alkaline earth metals form white precipitate with ammonium carbonate in the presence of ammonium chloride and ammonia.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The alkaline earth metal oxides are formed from the thermal decomposition of the corresponding carbonates.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] The oxides exhibit basic character: they turn phenolphthalein red and litmus, blue.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] They react with water to form hydroxides in an exothermic reaction.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium oxide reacts with carbon to form acetylide.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] They are generated from the corresponding oxides on reaction with water.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] They exhibit basic character: they turn phenolphthalein pink and litmus, blue.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium hydroxide is an exception as it exhibits amphoteric character.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Ca and Mg are found in nature in many compounds such as dolomite, aragonite, magnesite (carbonate rocks).
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium and magnesium ions are found in hard water.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Hard water represents a multifold issue.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] It is of great interest to remove these ions, thus softening the water.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] This procedure can be done using reagents such as calcium hydroxide, sodium carbonate or sodium phosphate.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium and calcium is essential to all known living organisms.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium is in plants, where it occurs in chlorophyll.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium ions play a large role in cell signaling, and calcium salts also take a structural role, most notably bones for vertebrates, and some shells in invertebrates.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium plays an important role in marine aquatic life, especially hard corals, which use strontium to build their exoskeletons.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] In medicine, strontium compounds are employed in some toothpastes to reduce dental hypersensitivity.
[src:carbide/alkaline-earth-metal] While strontium typically has a low toxicity, radioactive isotopes of strontium (like strontium-90) can be toxic.
